MD5SUM=${MD5SUM-md5sum}
f=`${MD5SUM} --version | egrep '^md5sum .*(core|text)utils'`
test -n "${f}" && md5check=true || md5check=false
${md5check} || \
  echo 'Note: not verifying md5sums.  Consider installing GNU coreutils.'
if test "X$1" = "X-c"
then keep_file=''
else keep_file=true
fi
echo=echo
save_IFS="${IFS}"
IFS="${IFS}:"
gettext_dir=
locale_dir=
set_echo=false

for dir in $PATH
do
  if test -f $dir/gettext \
     && ($dir/gettext --version >/dev/null 2>&1)
  then
    case `$dir/gettext --version 2>&1 | sed 1q` in
      *GNU*) gettext_dir=$dir
      set_echo=true
      break ;;
    esac
  fi
done

if ${set_echo}
then
  set_echo=false
  for dir in $PATH
  do
    if test -f $dir/shar \
       && ($dir/shar --print-text-domain-dir >/dev/null 2>&1)
    then
      locale_dir=`$dir/shar --print-text-domain-dir`
      set_echo=true
      break
    fi
  done

  if ${set_echo}
  then
    TEXTDOMAINDIR=$locale_dir
    export TEXTDOMAINDIR
    TEXTDOMAIN=sharutils
    export TEXTDOMAIN
    echo="$gettext_dir/gettext -s"
  fi
fi
IFS="$save_IFS"
if (echo "testing\c"; echo 1,2,3) | grep c >/dev/null
then if (echo -n test; echo 1,2,3) | grep n >/dev/null
     then shar_n= shar_c='
'
     else shar_n=-n shar_c= ; fi
else shar_n= shar_c='\c' ; fi
f=shar-touch.$$
st1=200112312359.59
st2=123123592001.59
st2tr=123123592001.5 # old SysV 14-char limit
st3=1231235901

if   touch -am -t ${st1} ${f} >/dev/null 2>&1 && \
     test ! -f ${st1} && test -f ${f}; then
  shar_touch='touch -am -t $1$2$3$4$5$6.$7 "$8"'

elif touch -am ${st2} ${f} >/dev/null 2>&1 && \
     test ! -f ${st2} && test ! -f ${st2tr} && test -f ${f}; then
  shar_touch='touch -am $3$4$5$6$1$2.$7 "$8"'

elif touch -am ${st3} ${f} >/dev/null 2>&1 && \
     test ! -f ${st3} && test -f ${f}; then
  shar_touch='touch -am $3$4$5$6$2 "$8"'

else
  shar_touch=:
  echo
  ${echo} 'WARNING: not restoring timestamps.  Consider getting and
installing GNU '\''touch'\'', distributed in GNU coreutils...'
  echo
fi
rm -f ${st1} ${st2} ${st2tr} ${st3} ${f}
#
if test ! -d ${lock_dir} ; then :
else ${echo} "lock directory ${lock_dir} exists"
     exit 1
fi
if mkdir ${lock_dir}
then ${echo} "x - created lock directory ${lock_dir}."
else ${echo} "x - failed to create lock directory ${lock_dir}."
     exit 1
fi
# ============= /home/agarciafdz/r/gh/elv79/elviejo79.github.io/2023-10-26-Algorithms-at-the-movies-angels-and-demons/index.md.html ==============
if test ! -d '/home'; then
  mkdir '/home'
if test $? -eq 0
then ${echo} "x - created directory /home."
else ${echo} "x - failed to create directory /home."
     exit 1
fi
fi
if test ! -d '/home/agarciafdz'; then
  mkdir '/home/agarciafdz'
if test $? -eq 0
then ${echo} "x - created directory /home/agarciafdz."
else ${echo} "x - failed to create directory /home/agarciafdz."
     exit 1
fi
fi
if test ! -d '/home/agarciafdz/r'; then
  mkdir '/home/agarciafdz/r'
if test $? -eq 0
then ${echo} "x - created directory /home/agarciafdz/r."
else ${echo} "x - failed to create directory /home/agarciafdz/r."
     exit 1
fi
fi
if test ! -d '/home/agarciafdz/r/gh'; then
  mkdir '/home/agarciafdz/r/gh'
if test $? -eq 0
then ${echo} "x - created directory /home/agarciafdz/r/gh."
else ${echo} "x - failed to create directory /home/agarciafdz/r/gh."
     exit 1
fi
fi
if test ! -d '/home/agarciafdz/r/gh/elv79'; then
  mkdir '/home/agarciafdz/r/gh/elv79'
if test $? -eq 0
then ${echo} "x - created directory /home/agarciafdz/r/gh/elv79."
else ${echo} "x - failed to create directory /home/agarciafdz/r/gh/elv79."
     exit 1
fi
fi
if test ! -d '/home/agarciafdz/r/gh/elv79/elviejo79.github.io'; then
  mkdir '/home/agarciafdz/r/gh/elv79/elviejo79.github.io'
if test $? -eq 0
then ${echo} "x - created directory /home/agarciafdz/r/gh/elv79/elviejo79.github.io."
else ${echo} "x - failed to create directory /home/agarciafdz/r/gh/elv79/elviejo79.github.io."
     exit 1

if test ! -d '/home/agarciafdz/r/gh/elv79/elviejo79.github.io/2023-10-26-Algorithms-at-the-movies-angels-and-demons'; then
  mkdir '/home/agarciafdz/r/gh/elv79/elviejo79.github.io/2023-10-26-Algorithms-at-the-movies-angels-and-demons'
if test $? -eq 0
then ${echo} "x - created directory /home/agarciafdz/r/gh/elv79/elviejo79.github.io/2023-10-26-Algorithms-at-the-movies-angels-and-demons."
else ${echo} "x - failed to create directory /home/agarciafdz/r/gh/elv79/elviejo79.github.io/2023-10-26-Algorithms-at-the-movies-angels-and-demons."
     exit 1

then
${echo} "x - SKIPPING /home/agarciafdz/r/gh/elv79/elviejo79.github.io/2023-10-26-Algorithms-at-the-movies-angels-and-demons/index.md.html (file already exists)"

else

X
2023-Oct-26: Algorithms at the Movies
======================================================
X
![Angels and Demons Movie Poster](./images/Angels_and_demons.jpg)
X
In the movie "Angels & Demons," there's a scene where an "antimatter bomb" is introduced. The prevailing idea is that once the antimatter comes into contact with matter, both the Vatican and Rome would vanish.
X
The Illuminati (the antagonists) send the police a live feed of the ticking bomb.
X
Camerlengo, the priestly manager of the Vatican (played by Ewan McGregor), suggests to the police that they should turn off the city's electricity, block by block, to identify the source of the live feed.
X
These constant shutdowns create challenges for Professor Langdon (Tom Hanks) and the scientist assisting him.
X
Upon watching the movie, I pondered: Why turn off the city lights block by block? That's a sequential algorithm! A Binary Search would be much more efficient.
X
Let's assume, for instance, that Rome has 64 blocks. Following the movie's sequential approach, there would be 64 blackouts. If each blackout lasts 1 minute, it would take more than one hour to find the bomb.
X
With Binary Search:
X
X
X
X
**************************
*                        *
*    * * * * * * * *     *
*    * * * * * * * *     *
*    * * * * * * * *     *
*    * * * * * * * *     *
*    * * * * * * * *     *
*    * * * * * * * *     *
*    * * * * * * * *     *
*    * * * * * * * *     *
*                        *
**************************
X
X
Turn off the electricity for the entire city (64 blocks) to ensure the bomb's lights are grid-connected. If they aren't, the blackout strategy is moot.
X
X
**************************
*                        *
*    * * * * o o o o     *
*    * * * * o o o o     *
*    * * * * o o o o     *
*    * * * * o o o o     *
*    * * * * o o o o     *
*    * * * * o o o o     *
*    * * * * o o o o     *
*    * * * * o o o o     *
*                        *
**************************
X
X
Assuming the chamber's lights go off, they would next shut down half the city's electricity (32 blocks). If the bomb's lights go off, then the correct half was chosen. If not, the bomb is in the other half.
X
X
X
X
X
X
**************************
*                        *
*    * * * * o o o o     *
*    * * * * o o o o     *
*    * * * * o o o o     *
*    * * * * o o o o     *
*    o o o o o o o o     *
*    o o o o o o o o     *
*    o o o o o o o o     *
*    o o o o o o o o     *
*                        *
**************************
X
X
Repeat the process with the selected half, then continue halving 5 more times (16, 8, 4, 2, 1) until the bomb's location is determined.
X
X
************************
*                      *
*    * * o o o o o o   *
*    * * o o o o o o   *
*    * * o o o o o o   *
*    * * o o o o o o   *
*    o o o o o o o o   *
*    o o o o o o o o   *
*    o o o o o o o o   *
*    o o o o o o o o   *
*                      *
************************
X
X
X
X
X
X
**************************
*                        *
*    * * o o o o o o     *
*    * * o o o o o o     *
*    o o o o o o o o     *
*    o o o o o o o o     *
*    o o o o o o o o     *
*    o o o o o o o o     *
*    o o o o o o o o     *
*    o o o o o o o o     *
*                        *
**************************
X
X
X
X
X
X
**************************
*                        *
*    * * o o o o o o     *
*    o o o o o o o o     *
*    o o o o o o o o     *
*    o o o o o o o o     *
*    o o o o o o o o     *
*    o o o o o o o o     *
*    o o o o o o o o     *
*    o o o o o o o o     *
*                        *
**************************
X
X
X
X
X
X
**************************
*                        *
*    * o o o o o o o     *
*    o o o o o o o o     *
*    o o o o o o o o     *
*    o o o o o o o o     *
*    o o o o o o o o     *
*    o o o o o o o o     *
*    o o o o o o o o     *
*    o o o o o o o o     *
*                        *
**************************
X
X
With this approach, the bomb can be located with just 7 blackouts (1 complete + 6 halves).
Crisis averted!
X
In this movie, the expert  symbologist Langdon wasn't necessary to save the city.
What they truly needed was a computer science...
student second-semester.
X

2023-Oct-28: Mortimer Adler How to Read a Book
======================================================
X
I read a heading I don't remember where that said:
X
> It doesn't matter how many books you read, what matters is how many summaries you write.
X
And I think there is a lot of truth to that sentence.
However even writing a summary is a lot of work,
So I need a way to produce summaries of books in a fast way.
X
Fortunately there is a book called "How to read a book"
By Mortimer Adler that I think is a master class on how to be an honest intellectual.
X
What follows is the summary of the How to read a book.
So that I can use it to produce summaries.
X
This one is taken from:
https://www.scribd.com/document/311241114/Adler-How-to-Read-a-Book
X
## 0. Systematic skimming or pre-reading
X
1. Look at the title page and preface, try to pigeonhole type of book.
1. Study the table of contents look for structure / roadmap for the trip.
1. Check the index try to estiate range of terms and topics; look up some passages that seem crucial.
1. Check the publishers blurb / summary of the book. Also the preface
1. Look for chapters whic seem most pivotal: read opening or closing pages carefully.
1. Thumb throught he entire book, reading a few paragraphs here and there, esp. at the en looking for the main arguments.
X
## 1. Superficial reading
X
1. Read thourugh "without ever stoppyng to lookup or ponder the things you do not understand right away"
1. "Go right on [until] you come to things you do understand. Concentrate on these. keep on this way." (e.g. reading Shakespeare!)
X
a. "Many book are hardly worth even skimming"
a. "some should be read quickly"
a. "a few should be read, quite slow... allowing for complete comprehension".. Like little sips.
X
Even difficult books have some material which can be read quickly.
X
a. "Race through even the hardest book". the first through.
a. "You will then be prepared to read it well the second time."
X
## 2. Inspectional reading
X
1. What is the book about as whole? Subject / classification
1. "What is being said in detail, and how?" Terms / interpretation
1. "Is the book true, in whole or part?" Truth / evaluation
1. "What of it?" Significance / Response
X
### Three kinds of note taking
X
a. Structural about the content of the subject
a. Conceptual about the truth and significance
a. Dilectical about the shape of the argument in the larger discussion of other peoples ideas.
X
## 3. Analytical Reading
X
### Fist stage of analytical reading
X
#### Rule 1. You must know what kind of book you are reading,
and you should know this as early in the process as possible, preferably before you begin to read. / Classify the book according to kind and subject matter. (p. 60)
X
#### Rule 2. State the unity of the whole book in a single sentence,
or at most a few sentences (a short paragraph). State what the whole book is about with the utmost brevity. (pp 75-76)
X
#### Rule 3. Set forth the major parts of the book, and show how these are organized into a whole,
by being ordered to one another nad the unity of the whole. / Enumerate its major parts in their order and relation, and outline these parts as you have outlined the whole. (p. 76)
X
#### Rule 4. Find out what the author's problems were.
Define the problem or problems the author has tried to solve. (p. 92)
X
### Second stage of analytical reading
X
#### Rule 5. Find the important words
and through them come to terms with the author. Come to terms with the author by interpreting his key words. (p. 98)
X 1. Find the key words (words which are emphasized, repeated, defined, and or italicized, 'fighting' words)
X 2. Find the meanings of those words from the context, like "putting a jigsaw puzzle together".
X
#### Rule 6. Mark the most important sentnces
in a book and discover the propositions they contain. Grasp the author's leading propositions by dealing with his most important sentences (p. 120)
X
#### Rule 7. Locate or construct the basic arguments
in the book, by connecting the sentences.
Know the author's arguments, by finding them in, or constructing them out of, sequences of sentences. (p. 120)
Arguments are statements which offer the grounds of reasn for the authors judgments and conclusions.
X
How to find the key sentences and propositions:
1. Look for signs: underlining; italics; location
1. look whele you seem to be "perplexed"
1. Look for statements containing key terms
1. look for a sequence in the arguments
1. separte complicated sentencs into more than one proposition
1. See if you can state the authors argument in your own words.
1. See if you can give your own expmplo to make the same point.
X
### Rule 8. Find out what the author's solutions are.
Determine which of his problems the author has solved, and which he has not;
and to the latter, decide whicho the author knew he had failed to solve. (p. 135)
X
### Third stage of analytical reading
#### Rule 9 You must be able to say 'I understand'.
Before you can say any of the following:
- I agree or I disagee or I suspend judgment.
Do not begin criticism until you have completed your outline and your interpretation of the book.
(pp 142- 143)
X
1. Recognize your respnosibility of taking a postion. in response to the propositions you have now read.
"Reading a book is a kind of conversation.. the author had hi say, and then is the readers turn"
X
2. Recognize the "role of rethoric" in this process, i.e. the attemn in all communication "to convince or presuade".
This attempt is "the ultimate end in view... rethoricla skill is knowing how to react to anyone who tries to convince or persuade us".
X
#### Rule 10. When you disagree, do so reasonably,
and not disputiously or contentiously. (p. 145)
X
#### Rule 11. Respect the difference between knwoldege and opnion, by giving reasons for your judgment.
(p. 150)
X
## Chapter 11 - Agreeing or disagreeing with an author
### Three ideal conditions for a well-conducted disagreement:
1. Acknowledge your emotions
1. Make your own assumptions explicit
1. Make an attempt at impartiability
### Foru practial ways to criticize a book negatively
1. You are uninformed
1. You are misinformed
1. You are illogical
1. Youy analysis is incomplete
X
## How to read practical books
What are he author's objectives and means?
X
### Chapter 14. How to read imaginative literature
Don't criticize until you fully appreciate...
X
### Chapter 15. Reading stories, plays and poems,
"Read quickly... suspend disbelief"
X
### Chapter 16. How to read history
Ask authors' purpose/audience/knowledge, etc.
X
### Chapter 17. Science and mathematics
Recognize math as a language to be learned
X
### Chapter 18. How to read philosophy
Identify question(s) and historical context
X
### Chapter 19. How to read social science
Identify point of view & mix of fact / fiction;
read syntopically (ie. in relation to other books on the same subject)
X
X
## Part 4: The ulitimate goals of reading
X
### Chapter 20. The 4th lever of reading, syntopical reading
X
#### A. The five steps of syntopical reading
X
1. Find the relevant passages
1. Establish a common terminology
1. Clarify the questions
1. Define the issues
1. Analyze  the discussion: Look for the truth:
X   a. In the order dicussion itself
X   b and in the conflict of opposing answers (weigh the evidence; seek to be objetive)
X
#### B. How to use the Syntopicon
A book  of 60 books called the great books of the world published by Encyclopedia Britannica.
Lists 103, Great Ideas (e.g. "Democracy God, Happiness")
X
### Chapter 21 Reading the Growth of the Mind
X
#### A. Active reading asking questions and looking for answers
X
#### B. What good books do for us?
X
- Stretch our mind
- improve our reading skill
- teach us about the world and ourselves
X
#### C. Difference btween good (few thousands) and great books (less than 100)
X
1. Good books need to have no more than one meaning and one reading
1. Great books have many meanings and need to be read over and over agin
X
#### D. The test of a great a book
X
1. "Marooned on a desert island": Which ten books would you select?
1. "The book seems to grow with you;" "you see new things" every time you re-read it; The book is able to "lift you" over and over again.
1. "You should seek out the few books that can have this value for you."
X
X
2023-Oct-28: How to read a book by Mortimer Adler
======================================================
X
Taken from this
https://www.scribd.com/document/360128823/Mortimer-Adler-How-to-Read-a-Book-pdf
X
## 1st stage Rules for finding what the book is about: What is the book about as whole?
X
1. Classify the book according to kind of subject matter.
2. State what the whole book is about with the utmost brevity.
3. Enumarate its major parts in their order and relation, and outline these parts as you have outlined the whole.
4. Define the problem or problems the author has tried to solve.
X
## 2nd stage: Rules for interpreting a Book's contents. What is being said in deail, and how?
X
5. Come to terms with the author by interpreting his keywords. Understand literally the words, terms that the author uses.
6. Grasp the author's leading propositons by dealing with his most important sentences.
7. Know the author's arguments, by finding them in, or constructing them out of, sequences of sentences.
8. Determine which of his problems the author has solved, and which he has not; and of the latter, decide which the authr knew he had faild to solve.
X
## 3rd stage: Rules for criticizing a book as a communication knowldege: Is it true? and what of it?
X
### A. General maxims of intellectual etiquette
X
9. Do not begin criticism until you have completed your outline and your interpretation of the book. Do not say you agree, disagree, or suspend judgment, until you can say "I understand")
10. Do not disagree diputatiously or contentiously.
11. Demonstrate that you recognize the difference between knowldege and mere personal opinion by presenting good reasons far any critical judgement you make.
X
### B. Special criteria for points of criticism
X
12. Is the author uninformed?
13. Is the author misinformed?
14. Is the author ilogical?
15. Is the author analyisis or account is incomplete?
X
Note: of these last four, the first three are criteria for disagreement. Failing in all of these, you must agree, at least in part, although you may suspend judgement on the whole, in light of the last point.
X
X
X
X
X
X
X
X
X
X

2023-Nov-2: How to brainstorm ideas.
==========================================================
This is my response to an stack exchange question:
X
https://ux.stackexchange.com/questions/69785/a-graph-system-for-drawing-conclusions/149126#149126
X
X
```
? How can a community of users draw conclusions together?
X ! They could use IBIS / Issue mapping
X   ? What is IBIS
X    ! Ibis is a syntax that was used in the 70s to help groups collaborate on wicked problems.
X     - But I don't want to use something from the 70s
X     + In the 90s they created an updated version of it based on computer interaction.
X     ? Where can I learn more about IBIS?
X       ! IBIS videos playlist: https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PL1IrP_dkJL9rQMtPN3ExxG5uVEHmvLFw4
X       ! IBIS books: https://www.goodreads.com/review/list/82326491-alejandro-garcia?shelf=ibis-dialogue-mapping
X       ! This blog: https://www.cleverworkarounds.com/2009/09/10/the-practice-of-dialogue-mapping-part-1/
X     ? Do you have an example of an IBIS map?
X       ! This answer!
X       ! the image at the top
X       ! the videos in the playlst
X
```
X
X
X
X
X
X
X
X

2023-Nov-18: keysentence
===========================================================
X
## Problem
X
The /huge real world probmel that clearly needs to be solved/;
/a specific knowledge-gap within the huge problem tha you lan to address in your project/
X
## Objective
X
With the /title - acronym/ project
we aim to /what the project is going to develop, achieve, discover, establish, improve, analyze to solve some part of the identified research gap,
to achive this aim, we have /number/ specific objectives.
X
1. /Develop, achieve, discove, establish, improve, analyze/ the objective of the first subproject.
2.
3.
X
## Methodology
X
During the project /description of research activity/ to /state what will the activity achieve/,
X
## Resources
X
The project will /use, apply, benefit from/ to /specific outcome/
X
## Participants
X
/Role/, /Person name/ from /affiliation/ is /core area fo expertise/ and has /proof of exepretices in terms of publications, projects, awards, etc./
X
## Results and impact
X
The project will /a general statement of what results, deliverables, outcomes the project will deliver to solve the problem you identified/, including:
X
- A statement of delivering a specific result/outcome in response to objective No. 1
- No. 2
- No. 3
X
Delivering these  results, outcomes will /enable, allow/ the, /specify the stakeholder/ to /explain what positive impacts these results/.
X
## Dissemination
X
We will /relevant activity/ the project results within /the key target audience/ through /the channels that you plan to use/.
X
## Timeline
X
The project will start in / date/, it will be executed in /number of months/, and /add the time when key reports, milestones, deliverables, other critical accomplisments will be submitted, reached/
X
## Budget
X
The total eligible projects costs are /the sum/ where /name the cost for each cost category as requested in the research call guide/.
Name of partners 1 will use x% of the budget,
Describe the co-financing by the partners, if any
XX% of the costs are covered through the fund if already known.
X
X
X
2023-Nov-18: On how to write a research grant key sentences
===========================================================
The big problem is that ___ evidence ___
We should solve it because ___ evidence ___
we already know that ___ evidence ___
we need to find out ___ evidence ___
we already know that __ evidence ___
we need to find out ___ evidence ____
Our apprach is pertinent because ___ evidence ___
Filling the knowldege gap will help to ___
X
X
X
X
X
X
X
X
X

X              <meta charset="utf-8" emacsmode="-*- markdown -*-">
X
X                            **A personal knoledge filesystem**
X
2023-Nov-22: Knowledge Filesystem
===========================================================
There is an explosion on what are called thiniking tools (Roam, Obsidian, etc.) evidence ____
However most of this tools store their knowledge base as markdown notes.
But our the nodes oun our  knowledge come in many forms:
- Images, Videos, Bookmarks, PDFs, etc.
So we need to create system that allows for the storage and liking of all the information we already posses.
In order to gain the benefits of a truly personal knowledge graph.
X
There have been attempts in the past to create a Filesystem that works more like a databes of Atributes than as a tree of files and directories.
starting with BeOS, and also DeepFS and even Windows 7 had an attempt to provide that.
And we al so have the NHFS to tag files using different attributes as folders.
X
However, those approaches are not popular.
So there is a need for a graph filesystem that can represent a knowledge graph
but we think those approaches were not successful for the following reasons:
X
1. They have usabulity problems (as is theorized on the thesis....)
2. They have reliability problems (i.e. they might loose files)
3. They have bad integration with common unix tools such as cp, mv, etc.
4. There is not a protection warranty about the storage of the files.
X
However several improvements in the past years make this goal worth revisiting.
X
1. The Eiffel programming language and Invariants in Design By Contract,
X   make developing a realiable filesystem a lot easier than the current state of the practice which is Python and C++
X
2. The developmente of test suite with 100,000 of tests that we can use as an oracle to validate our implementation
3. The deveolpment of a verified filesystem.
4. The content indexing of files using Inter Planetary FileSystem (IPFS).
5. The explosion in the use of the Zettelkasten method and the so called thinking tools.
X
So maybe Personal Knowledge Graph Filesystem is an idea whose time has come.
And we intend to find out, by building a truly reliable system.
That can last for generations.
X
X
X
<link rel="stylesheet" href="https://morgan3d.github.io/markdeep/latest/latex.css?">

Unraveling the Complexities of Patents: A Case Study of Sawstop
================================================================
X
## Introduction: The Intersection of Innovation and Intellectual Property
In the realm of patents and their impact on technological advancement, one invention stands out for its significance: the Sawstop.
X
## Understanding Sawstop: A Safety Revolution in Carpentry
### What Makes Sawstop Remarkable?
Imagine a table saw that can distinguish between wood and a human finger, and stops instantaneously to prevent injuries. That's the magic of Sawstop. It's a breakthrough in carpentry, designed to halt automatically and prevent amputation upon detecting a finger.
X
### A Stark Reality in Workshop Safety
Statistics reveal a grim picture: annually, table saws are involved in about 60,000 accidents, leading to roughly 3,000 amputations. Sawstop's relevance is undeniable.
X
### The Inventor's Confidence: A Real-Life Demonstration
Daringly, the inventor demonstrated the technology's reliability by risking his own finger.
[Experience the dramatic demonstration here](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XVktVFyid-Y).
X
## The Patent Conundrum
### Why Isn't Every Table Saw a Sawstop?
The answer lies in the web of patents. The inventor, leveraging his expertise in physics and law, secured over 100 patents for Sawstop, creating a significant barrier for competitors.
X
### Bosch's Legal Struggle: A Spotlight on Patent Issues
The case of Bosch, who faced legal action from Sawstop for developing a similar safety feature, illustrates the intricate and often contentious nature of patent law.
X
## Beyond Black and White: The Shades of Patent Reality
### The Journey of Sawstop
Rejected by major manufacturers, the inventor embarked on a solo journey, establishing a factory to produce Sawstop. The company, sold in 2017, is now a success story, yet its revolutionary technology remains underutilized.
X
### The Persistent Safety Challenge
Despite Sawstop's achievements, the widespread occurrence of table saw accidents and amputations continues, highlighting a gap in technology adoption.
X
## Patent Ethics and Societal Impact: A Deeper Dive
### Volvo's Seatbelt Precedent: Open-Source for Public Safety
Volvo's decision to freely share its seatbelt patent starkly contrasts with Sawstop's strategy. This raises a question: does open-sourcing life-saving technology lead to swifter, widespread adoption?
X
### Key Questions in the Patent Debate
- Should Sawstop have followed Volvo's footsteps in open-sourcing its patents?
- Did major tool companies miss a crucial opportunity by not licensing Sawstop's technology?
- Is it the government's role to mandate such safety innovations?
- Is the issue deeper, rooted in the foundations of intellectual property or capitalism?
X
### Future Prospects: Post-Patent Possibilities
With the expiration of Sawstop's patents in 2026, we might witness a new era of safety innovations in carpentry tools.
X
### The Promise of Emerging Technologies
Emerging safety solutions, like those using computer vision, offer a glimpse into a future possibly free from patent restrictions.
[Explore an innovative approach here](https://www.youtube.com/shorts/2AFQPkDMJmU).
X
## Concluding Thoughts: Patents and the Path Forward
The Sawstop saga is more than a story about a revolutionary safety device; it's a case study in the intricate dance of patents, innovation, and societal benefit. As we ponder the future of such technologies, the interplay between intellectual property, corporate responsibility, and public safety remains a compelling narrative in the ever-evolving story of human ingenuity.
X
X

X

X                          ** My Idea of an IBIS Languga**
X
IBIS is a way to map conversations and dialogues to solve, wicked problems.
I'm a big fan of it, because that is how my brain works.
However I don't like the point and click tools to create IBIS maps.
I rather write them as conversations.
X
This is my working map of what it.
X
X
## The goal
X
### First version
X
#### I want to type this:
X
```
Why is there no silver bullet in software engineering?
X Silve Bullet: any software engineering development that can produce a tenfold or better improvement in programming productivity.
X Essential difficulties : Those related to conceptualization design !
X What silver bullets have been proposed to date?
X
```
X
#### When the formating happens
But I want the code editor, when it does the reformating to show this:
X
```
? Why is there no silver bullet in software engineering?
X . Silver Bullet: any software engineering development that can produce a tenfold or better improvement in programming productivity.
X * Essential difficulties : Those related to conceptualization design
X ? What silver bullets have been proposed to date?
```
X
Notice that it kind of re-organizes the code, putting the question first... and the id ...
because when I start typing I'm not 100% sure if its a proporsar or an idea.
the
X
`.` is used to represent note?? mabye not... I want to be able to add details to a node, like links and stuff.. but not too many nodes. (maybe like icons surrounding the text?
`!` is used to represent an idea
`?` is used to represent a question)
X
#### I want to see
X
[1st version of map](https://eight2late.files.wordpress.com/2009/04/no_silver_bullet_stage11.jpg)
X
X
### 2nd verion
X
Once I have the first version the map can grow like this:
X
```
? Why is there no silver bullet in software engineering?
X . Silver Bullet: any software engineering development that can produce a tenfold or better improvement in programming productivity.
X * Essential difficulties : Those related to conceptualization design
X    What are the essential difficultios of designing software?
X        * Complexity: no two parts alike; many states; nonlinear interactions between modules.
X        * Comformity: must conform to arbritray conditions (business rules, existin systems)
X        * Changeability: often required to change difficulty of change understimated.
X        * Invisibility: structure cannot be vsualized (flowcharts and visual modelling languages are very limited)
X ? What silver bullets have been proposed to date?
```
X
#### The autoforamtter
X
Would of course change it to icons first:
X
``` yaml
? Why is there no silver bullet in software engineering?
X . Silver Bullet: any software engineering development that can produce a tenfold or better improvement in programming productivity.
X * Essential difficulties : Those related to conceptualization design
X    ? What are the essential difficultios of designing software?
X        * Complexity: no two parts alike; many states; nonlinear interactions between modules.
X        * Comformity: must conform to arbritray conditions (business rules, existin systems)
X        * Changeability: often required to change difficulty of change understimated.
X        * Invisibility: structure cannot be vsualized (flowcharts and visual modelling languages are very limited)
X ? What silver bullets have been proposed to date?
X
```
X

X    Notice that it seems that the colons are the id... maybe something to consider for when I need to use ids to reference other sentences

What I want to see:

### 3rd edition
X
Now the important thing... sometimes the pros and cons are the same
X
#### I want to write
X
``` yaml
? Why is there no silver bullet in software engineering?
X . Silver Bullet: any software engineering development that can produce a tenfold or better improvement in programming productivity.
X * Essential difficulties : Those related to conceptualization design
X    ? What are the essential difficultios of designing software?
X        * Complexity: no two parts alike; many states; nonlinear interactions between modules.
X        * Comformity: must conform to arbritray conditions (business rules, existin systems)
X        * Changeability: often required to change difficulty of change understimated.
X        * Invisibility: structure cannot be vsualized (flowcharts and visual modelling languages are very limited)
X ? What silver bullets have been proposed to date?
X    * These address indcidental difficulties (those related to implementation).
X         for example?
X            * OOP
X                + Improved programmer productivity (ipp)
X                - Do not help in software design (nodesing)
X            * Better Hardware
X                # ipp ---- notice that I mean a reference to the same above
X                # nodesign ----notice that I mean a reference to the one above (so a pro and a con the same way)
X            * High level languages
X                # ipp
X                # nodesign
X            * Better tools - IDEs, etc.
X                # ipp
X                # no design
X            * AI / Expert systems
X                - limited applicability (la)
X                # no design
X            * Program Verification
X                # la
```
X
##### But the auto formatter should show:
X
``` yaml
? Why is there no silver bullet in software engineering?
X . Silver Bullet: any software engineering development that can produce a tenfold or better improvement in programming productivity.
X * Essential difficulties : Those related to conceptualization design
X    ? What are the essential difficultios of designing software?
X        * Complexity: no two parts alike; many states; nonlinear interactions between modules.
X        * Comformity: must conform to arbritray conditions (business rules, existin systems)
X        * Changeability: often required to change difficulty of change understimated.
X        * Invisibility: structure cannot be vsualized (flowcharts and visual modelling languages are very limited)
X ? What silver bullets have been proposed to date?
X    * These address indcidental difficulties (those related to implementation).
X         for example?
X            * OOP
X                + &ipp Improved programmer productivity
X                - &nodesign Do not help in software design
X            * Better Hardware
X                + *ipp ---- notice that I mean a reference to the same above
X                - *nodesign ----notice that I mean a reference to the one above (so a pro and a con the same way)
X            * High level languages
X                + *ipp
X                - *nodesign
X            * Better tools - IDEs, etc.
X                + *ipp
X                - *no design
X            * AI / Expert systems
X                - &la limited applicability
X                - *nodesign
X            * Program Verification
X                - *la
```
X
X
Obeserve that the pros and cons are insert with the correct sign.
this is because a pro can be a con in another... this is common.
X
X
##### How it should look
X

# My problem a deadlock.
X
The problem that I've had is that I've been deadlocked in search for that tool.
X
```
I want to do many things.
I need to write what I want to do in file.
There are dependencies between things
I need to map the dependencies as graph datastructure.
I want to visualize the graph datastructure as a diagram.
You can use any diagram editor for that.
I **want** to write in text, and visualize in diagram
So I'll add to my list of projects.
I want to do many things, an the cycle begins again!
```
X
So  I need to break that cycle.
X
``` ibis
? How can I break the deadlock of organizing my mind?
X    * use a tool that already exists, until you can develop your own
? What alternatives do I have? (aggghhh I want to put this nested but it doesn't work)
X    * Dot/graphviz
X        + It works now and is stable
X        + It can handle subgraphs
X        + it can have infinite customization.
X        - I don't like the syntax
X            ? Why?
X                * it forces to wre the nodes first and later the edges.
X                * it mixes presentation with content
X    * Use Flyinglogic
X        + I <3 the way it looks
X        - It is monthly payment.
X        - I can't insert the diagrams in other documents
X        - I can't present the diagrams in order.
X        - I can't create the diagram from keyboard only
X    * Plantuml
X        it has the same disadvantages as Dot/grahpviz (this should be a pointer)
X    * Use yaml to create a DSL
X        + It works today
X        + it is whitespace based
X        + it favors a tree representation
X        + it can *copy* from one branch to another
X        + Related, it supports defining ids with the &ampresnand operator and reference with *operator.
X        + can be edited in vscode and lapce and many other editors
X        + with the redhat extension supports json-schema
X        - Dosn't have a native graph representation
X            ? How can you provide that?
X                * Transform yaml to json |> jsonata |> (diagramming tool: glsp, graphx, d3, cytoscope)
X        - it already uses the characters (-) that I want to use for my language
X            ? How can you solve that?
X                * use complete word + == pros, - == cons, & == id, * == reference
X        ! Deal: this is te option I'm going to use
X            ? how?
X                * create json-schema that forces correct use symbols
X                * use an editor like vscode, lapce, doomemacs that have auto complete.
X                * find a graphvusalization tool, and produce the json that it uses.
X                * use watch in the filesystem so that the graphvisualization gets updated automatically.
X
```
X
!!! Note
X    One of the things that makes treeNotation special is that we can mix grammars.
X    for example the prevous code, could be just a line called ibisLanguage
X    and everything nested below it would be parsed using the ibis grammar!
X    and then maybe ibisLanguage asHTML would parse the content, and then transform it to HTML...
X

## Now let's try with a yaml document
X
So I have takeng the json-graph examples here:
https://raw.githubusercontent.com/jsongraph/json-graph-specification/master/examples/usual_suspects.json
X
And transformed it to yaml so it looks like this
X
``` yaml
#yaml-language-server: $schema=https://jsongraphformat.info/v2.0/json-graph-schema.json
X
graph:
X  id: Usual Suspects
X  type: movie characters
X  label: Usual Suspects
X  nodes:
X    Roger Kint:
X      label: Roger Kint
X      metadata:
X        nickname: Verbal
X        actor: Kevin Spacey
X    Keyser Sze:
X      label: Keyser Sze
X      metadata:
X        actor: Kevin Spacey
X  edges:
X  - source: Roger Kint
X    target: Keyser Sze
X    relation: is
X  metadata:
X    release year: '1995'
X
```
X
and it works!! it validates the document!!
uff...
X
## A Visualization with cytoscape
Now we can take that json...
And visualize it using cytoscape.
X
Like in this link
file://./test/visualize_a_basic_usual_suspects_json.html?graphUrl=https://raw.githubusercontent.com/jsongraph/json-graph-specification/master/examples/les_miserables.json
X
Observe that to the webpage I send as parameters the url of the json, that is the example
`?graphUrl=https://raw.githubusercontent.com/jsongraph/json-graph-specification/master/examples/les_miserables.json`
X
That page is just used to execute the javascript
that reads the json data and visualize its using js.cytoscape.org to view it.
Here is the algorithm.
X
X
``` html
<html>
<head>
X    <title>My Graph</title>
X    <script src="https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/cytoscape/3.19.0/cytoscape.min.js"></script>
</head>
<body>
X    <div id="cy" style="width: 800px; height: 600px;"></div>
X    <script type="text/javascript">
X        // Function to get the URL parameter
X        function getGraphUrlParameter() {
X            const queryString = window.location.search;
X            const urlParams = new URLSearchParams(queryString);
X            return urlParams.get('graphUrl');
X        }
X
X        // Get the graph URL from the query parameter
X        const graphUrl = getGraphUrlParameter();
X
X    fetch(graphUrl)
X    .then(response => response.json())
X    .then(rawData => {
X        // Transform nodes
X        const nodes = Object.keys(rawData.graph.nodes).map(key => {
X            return {
X                data: {
X                    id: key,
X                    ...rawData.graph.nodes[key]
X                }
X            };
X        });
X
X        // Transform edges
X        const edges = rawData.graph.edges.map(edge => {
X            return {
X                data: edge
X            };
X        });
X
X        // Combine nodes and edges
X        const elements = nodes.concat(edges);
X
X        // Initialize Cytoscape
X        var cy = cytoscape({
X            container: document.getElementById('cy'),
X            elements: elements,
X            style: [/* define your style here */],
X            layout: {/* define your layout here */}
X        });
X    })
X    .catch(error => {
X        console.error('Error fetching the graph data:', error);
X    });
X
X    </script>
</body>
</html>
```
X

## Jsonata to transform jsong-graph example to a version that cytoscape uses
X
In yesterday's example I don't like that code uses:
X
``` js
X.then(rawData => {
X        // Transform nodes
X        const nodes = Object.keys(rawData.graph.nodes).map(key => {
X            return {
X                data: {
X                    id: key,
X                    ...rawData.graph.nodes[key]
X                }
X            };
X        });
X
X        // Transform edges
X        const edges = rawData.graph.edges.map(edge => {
X            return {
X                data: edge
X            };
X        });
X
X        // Combine nodes and edges
X        const elements = nodes.concat(edges);
```
There is nothing wrong with the code,
but I prefer https://jsonata.org for all my json filtering and transformations.
I think that way the query can be resued in another page.
Or can even be shorter.
X
## Jsoata attempts
Given this json-graph
https://raw.githubusercontent.com/jsongraph/json-graph-specification/master/examples/les_miserables.json
X
I want to transform it to something close to this:
X
X
``` js
$.graph.id@$graph_title{
X    "edges":$.edges.{
X        "data":$
X    },
X    "nodes":$.nodes.$keys()@$id.*.{
X        "data":{
X            "id":$id,
X            "label":$.label,
X            "classes":[$.metadata.group.$string()],
X            "parent":$graph_title
X        }
X    }
X
}
```
X
### Now I have a new version of the jsonata query that assemblys the result in parts:
X
``` js
X        const qryJsongraphV2ToCytoscape = `
X        (
$root := $.graph{
X    "data":{
X        "id": id,
X        "label": id,
X        "title": type,
X        "how_to_copy":metadata
X    }
};
X
$nodes := $.graph.nodes.$keys()@$id.*.{
X        "data":{
X            "id":$id,
X            "label":$.label,
X            "classes":[$.metadata.group.$string()],
X            "parent":$$.graph.title
X        }
X    } ;
X
$edges := $.graph.edges.{"data":$};
X
/* We assembly the object that is going to be the one returned by the query */
{
X    "nodes":$append($root,$nodes),
X    "edges":$edges
}
)        
X        `;
```
X
I know, that query looks bigger than the code that it's replacing,
but it does more things.
it is preparing the graph to be displayed using nest graphs.
X

# Saturday December 16

## Let's improve the jsonata query
X
As part of the transormation for the json.
I still think the query is too complex
In particular this part
X
``` javascript
$n := graph.nodes.*.{
X    "id":label,
X    "kind":"node",
X    "label":label,
X    "desc":" ",
X    "tags":["transformar el metadata a array the key:value"],
X    "parent":"id of thee graph that represents the root",
X    "backgroundImageURL":null,
X    "has_dynamic_notes":false,
X    "is_collapsed":false
};
```
X
the ` "id": label` is unsatisfactory because
it shouldn't be the label it should be the ID
that is the name of the object.
X
### How to insert the id as part of the object
so to make the id as part of the node we can use the each and transfrom operators
X
``` javascript
graph.nodes.
X    $each(function($n, $id) {
X    /* currently a node is of the form id:node_object */
X    /* we want the node_objet to contain the id itself */
X    $n~>|$|{"id":$id}|
X    })
X
```
X
The `$each` functios splits in value and keys
then we use the transform opertar
to take the node, and just add the "id" field
to it.
the rest of fields in the node are automatically
added to $n.
X
with that correction now the section looks like this:
X
``` javascript
$n:=graph.nodes.
X    $each(function($n, $id) {
X    /* notice: we are injecting the id into the node */
X    $merge([$n,{"id":$id}])
X    }).
X    {
X    /*notice: now we use the that comes with the node */
X    "id":id,
X    "kind":"node",
X    "label":label,
X    "desc":" ",
X    /* notice: we use the metadata as tags */
X    "tags":$each(metadata, function($v, $k) {$k & ":" & $v}),
X    "parent":"id of thee graph that represents the root",
X    "backgroundImageURL":null,
X    "has_dynamic_notes":false,
X    "is_collapsed":false
X    }
```
X
### Stedi a new playground for jsonata queries:
+ It saves the contents of the frames as part of the URL, so we don't loose it
+ it is easy to share a link to the query
- The debugger gives a wrong position for the error messages.
X

### Next version of the whole jsonata query
In stedy https://stedi.link/kdqY6J0
X
But since I don't want to loose my query here is the backup
X
``` javascript
(
$node_template:=function($id,$label,$metadata,$parentId){{
X    "id":$id,
X    "kind":"node",
X    "label":$label,
X    "desc":" ",
X    "tags":[$each($metadata, function($v, $k) {$k & ":" & $v})],
X    "parent":$parentId,
X    "backgroundImageURL":null,
X    "has_dynamic_notes":false,
X    "is_collapsed":false
X  }
};
X
$rootNode := graph.($node_template(id,label,metadata,null));
X
X
X $n:=graph.nodes.
X    $each(function($n, $id) {
X    /* notice: we are injecting the id into the node */
X    $merge([$n,{"id":$id}])
X    }).(
X      $node_template(id,label,metadata,$rootNode.id)
X    )
X    ;
X
$e:=graph.edges.{
X    "id":source&"-"&target,
X    "kind":"edge",
X    "label":relation,
X    "desc":"desc",
X    "tags":[],
X    "directed":relation?true:false,
X    "weight":metadata.value,
X    "fromId":source,
X    "toId":target
};
X
$const_theme := {
X    "name": "minimal",
X    "bgfill": "#e5e7eb",
X    "grid": false,
X    "snapdist": {
X      "x": 100,
X      "y": 100
X    },
X    "selectionColor": "#1f2937",
X    "highlightColor": "red",
X    "nodefill": "white",
X    "nodelabelstroke": "black",
X    "nodelabelfontsize": 16,
X    "nodenotesfontsize": 16,
X    "nodeborder": "black",
X    "nodeborderradius": 15,
X    "nodeBackgroundImageURL": null,
X    "edgestroke": "#1f2937",
X    "edgeshape": "curved",
X    "edgestroketype": "solid",
X    "font": "PT Mono",
X    "badges": [
X      "",
X      "",
X      "",
X      "",
X      ""
X    ]
X  },
X  "jsondownload": true,
X  "jsonupload": true,
X  "contextmenu": true,
X  "customjson": false,
X  "exportcytoscape": true,
X  "exportsvg": true,
X  "title": "Sample graph",
X  "description": "Compound graphs allow nodes to be nested inside each other.",
X  "contact": "mailto:eshnil22@gmail.com"
};
X
$grapherx_formatted:={
X    "items":$append($rootNode,$n)~>$append($e)},
X    "theme":$const_theme
X    };
)
```

## Nested graphs
X
``` yaml
- items:
X  - type: Questions
X    id: root
X    title: What should we do about the one ring?
X    items:
X      - type: answers
X        id: gg
X        title: Give it to golumm
X        items:
X          - type: Questions
X      
X            id: addicted
X            title: Isn't he addicted to the ring?
X            items:
X              - type: answers
X                id: ay 
X                title: Yes,but so what?
X                items: 
X                  - type: Questions
X              
X                    id: yw
X                    title: So what??!! 
X      - type: answers
X        id: gh
X        title: Give it to humans
X        items:
X          - type: pros 
X            id: weapon
X            title: use the enemys weapon against itself
X          - type: pros 
X            id: deserve
X            title: we deserve it. 
X          - type: cons
X            id: greed
X            title: humans greed has failled us once before.
X      - type: answers
X        id: bm
X        title: Burn it in mount mordor
X        items:
X          - type: pros 
X            id: ow
X            title: its the only way to destroy it
X          - type: cons
X            id: rd
X            title: the road is extremely dangerous
```

## Monday dey 18
X
I have finally created a query that transforms the previous json
into a nested structure by types.
X
Here is the result.
As you can see it has the yaml from yesterday as json
then two jsonata queries
https://try.jsonata.org/ZX5swwLNE
X
the one that I think is the best is:
X
` $groupSentencesByTypeAndId`
X
``` json
( 
/* 
$groupByType:=function($tree){
X    $tree.items{
X        `type`:$.($merge([{id:title},$groupByType($)]))
X    }
};
X
$groupByType($);
*/
X
$groupSentencesByTypeAndId:=function($tree){
X    $tree.items{
X    /* Question, Ideao, etc. will be a hashmap of things of that type*/
X    /* the hasmap will be identified by id*/
X    `type`:{`id`:
X                /* for each one of the sentences, create an object */
X                $.($merge([
X                            {"id":id,"title":title},
X                            /* if the sentence has its own children then also nest those */
X                            $groupSentencesByTypeAndId($)
X                            ])
X                    )
X            }
X    }
};
X
$groupSentencesByTypeAndId($)
)
```
X
However I'll need to check, because some times it seems I'm figthing jsonata a little bit.
X
Now let's see how it works in the command line
X
``` bash
X
$ cat ./src/ex4.list_of_objects.yaml | jfq --accept-yaml --query-file ./src/groupSentencesByTypeAndId.jsonata  > ./srex4.byTypeAndId.json
X
```
X
Now in `ex4.byTypeAndId.json` we can see the structure.
It looks well
Although I think that maky jsonata want to use
arrays for nested structures instead of
hashmaps.
X
this is something I'll need to keep in mind.
X
### Sentnces only by type and as array
X
Since I suspect that working with nested arrays
is a more natural way to work with jsonata
X
I also made another query:
X
https://try.jsonata.org/XUnlg-DC7
X
``` json
(
X
$groupByType:=function($tree){
X    $tree.items{
X        `type`:$.($merge([{"id":id, "title":title},$groupByType($)]))
X    }
};
X
$groupByType($);
)
```
X
X
then executing the query like this
``` bash
X
$ cat ./src/ex4.list_of_objects.yaml | jfq --accept-yaml --query-file ./src/groupSentencesByType.jsonata  > ./src/ex4.byType.json
X
```
Gives us a new json
X

### Subsection on stuff
X
X
Thing Name              | Description        |Notes
------------------------|--------------------|-----
Yes                     | Yup!               |
No                      | Nope :(            |
FileNotFound            | Doesn't find files | Pass `-sFIND_FILE=maybe` to maybe find them

## Markdeep syntax test
X
Regular styling like **bold**, _italics_, ~~strikethrough~~, `inline code`, the stuff.
X
X
Symbol substitutions: a 45-degree turn; som x -> y arrows; some whoa ==> fancy <==> arrows.
X
Is this a definition list?
:   Looks like one to me
Is that right?
:   Possibly!
X
And a code listing:
X
X~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
int main()
{
X    return 1;
}
X~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

X                          ** My Idea of an IBIS Languga**
X
IBIS is a way to map conversations and dialogues to solve, wicked problems.
I'm a big fan of it, because that is how my brain works.
However I don't like the point and click tools to create IBIS maps.
I rather write them as conversations.
X
This is my working map of what it.
X
X
## The goal
X
### First version
X
#### I want to type this:
X
```
@@ex1/mytyping
```
X
#### When the formating happens
But I want the code editor, when it does the reformating to show this:
X
```
@@ex1/reformated
```
X
Notice that it kind of re-organizes the code, putting the question first... and the id ...
because when I start typing I'm not 100% sure if its a proporsar or an idea.
the
X
`.` is used to represent note?? mabye not... I want to be able to add details to a node, like links and stuff.. but not too many nodes. (maybe like icons surrounding the text?
`!` is used to represent an idea
`?` is used to represent a question)
X
#### I want to see
X
[1st version of map](https://eight2late.files.wordpress.com/2009/04/no_silver_bullet_stage11.jpg)
X
X
### 2nd verion
X
Once I have the first version the map can grow like this:
X
```
@@ex2/mytyping
```
X
#### The autoforamtter
X
Would of course change it to icons first:
X
``` yaml
@@ex2/reformatted
```
X
!!! Note
X    Notice that it seems that the colons are the id... maybe something to consider for when I need to use ids to reference other sentences
X
#### The image
What I want to see:
X
[2nd iteration](https://eight2late.files.wordpress.com/2009/04/no_silver_bullet_stage4.jpg?w=700&h=729)
X
X
### 3rd edition
X
Now the important thing... sometimes the pros and cons are the same
X
#### I want to write
X
``` yaml
@@ex3/mytyping
```
X
##### But the auto formatter should show:
X
``` yaml
@@ex3/reformatted
```
X
X
Obeserve that the pros and cons are insert with the correct sign.
this is because a pro can be a con in another... this is common.
X
X
##### How it should look
X
[3rd](https://eight2late.files.wordpress.com/2009/04/no_silver_bullet_stage4.jpg?w=700&h=729)

# My problem a deadlock.
X
The problem that I've had is that I've been deadlocked in search for that tool.
X
```
I want to do many things.
I need to write what I want to do in file.
There are dependencies between things
I need to map the dependencies as graph datastructure.
I want to visualize the graph datastructure as a diagram.
You can use any diagram editor for that.
I **want** to write in text, and visualize in diagram
So I'll add to my list of projects.
I want to do many things, an the cycle begins again!
```
X
So  I need to break that cycle.
X
``` ibis
? How can I break the deadlock of organizing my mind?
X    * use a tool that already exists, until you can develop your own
? What alternatives do I have? (aggghhh I want to put this nested but it doesn't work)
X    * Dot/graphviz
X        + It works now and is stable
X        + It can handle subgraphs
X        + it can have infinite customization.
X        - I don't like the syntax
X            ? Why?
X                * it forces to wre the nodes first and later the edges.
X                * it mixes presentation with content
X    * Use Flyinglogic
X        + I <3 the way it looks
X        - It is monthly payment.
X        - I can't insert the diagrams in other documents
X        - I can't present the diagrams in order.
X        - I can't create the diagram from keyboard only
X    * Plantuml
X        it has the same disadvantages as Dot/grahpviz (this should be a pointer)
X    * Use yaml to create a DSL
X        + It works today
X        + it is whitespace based
X        + it favors a tree representation
X        + it can *copy* from one branch to another
X        + Related, it supports defining ids with the &ampresnand operator and reference with *operator.
X        + can be edited in vscode and lapce and many other editors
X        + with the redhat extension supports json-schema
X        - Dosn't have a native graph representation
X            ? How can you provide that?
X                * Transform yaml to json |> jsonata |> (diagramming tool: glsp, graphx, d3, cytoscope)
X        - it already uses the characters (-) that I want to use for my language
X            ? How can you solve that?
X                * use complete word + == pros, - == cons, & == id, * == reference
X        ! Deal: this is te option I'm going to use
X            ? how?
X                * create json-schema that forces correct use symbols
X                * use an editor like vscode, lapce, doomemacs that have auto complete.
X                * find a graphvusalization tool, and produce the json that it uses.
X                * use watch in the filesystem so that the graphvisualization gets updated automatically.
X
```
X
!!! Note
X    One of the things that makes treeNotation special is that we can mix grammars.
X    for example the prevous code, could be just a line called ibisLanguage
X    and everything nested below it would be parsed using the ibis grammar!
X    and then maybe ibisLanguage asHTML would parse the content, and then transform it to HTML...
X

So now that I have found what I want to do let's do it!

## Jsonata to transform jsong-graph example to a version that cytoscape uses
X
In yesterday's example I don't like that code uses:
X
``` js
X.then(rawData => {
X        // Transform nodes
X        const nodes = Object.keys(rawData.graph.nodes).map(key => {
X            return {
X                data: {
X                    id: key,
X                    ...rawData.graph.nodes[key]
X                }
X            };
X        });
X
X        // Transform edges
X        const edges = rawData.graph.edges.map(edge => {
X            return {
X                data: edge
X            };
X        });
X
X        // Combine nodes and edges
X        const elements = nodes.concat(edges);
```
There is nothing wrong with the code,
but I prefer https://jsonata.org for all my json filtering and transformations.
I think that way the query can be resued in another page.
Or can even be shorter.
X
## Jsoata attempts
Given this json-graph
https://raw.githubusercontent.com/jsongraph/json-graph-specification/master/examples/les_miserables.json
X
I want to transform it to something close to this:
X
X
``` js
$.graph.id@$graph_title{
X    "edges":$.edges.{
X        "data":$
X    },
X    "nodes":$.nodes.$keys()@$id.*.{
X        "data":{
X            "id":$id,
X            "label":$.label,
X            "classes":[$.metadata.group.$string()],
X            "parent":$graph_title
X        }
X    }
X
}
```

# Saturday December 16
X
## Let's improve the jsonata query
X
As part of the transormation for the json.
I still think the query is too complex
In particular this part
X
``` javascript
$n := graph.nodes.*.{
X    "id":label,
X    "kind":"node",
X    "label":label,
X    "desc":" ",
X    "tags":["transformar el metadata a array the key:value"],
X    "parent":"id of thee graph that represents the root",
X    "backgroundImageURL":null,
X    "has_dynamic_notes":false,
X    "is_collapsed":false
};
```
X
the ` "id": label` is unsatisfactory because
it shouldn't be the label it should be the ID
that is the name of the object.
X
### How to insert the id as part of the object
so to make the id as part of the node we can use the each and transfrom operators
X
``` javascript
graph.nodes.
X    $each(function($n, $id) {
X    /* currently a node is of the form id:node_object */
X    /* we want the node_objet to contain the id itself */
X    $n~>|$|{"id":$id}|
X    })
X
```
X
The `$each` functios splits in value and keys
then we use the transform opertar
to take the node, and just add the "id" field
to it.
the rest of fields in the node are automatically
added to $n.
X
with that correction now the section looks like this:
X
``` javascript
$n:=graph.nodes.
X    $each(function($n, $id) {
X    /* notice: we are injecting the id into the node */
X    $merge([$n,{"id":$id}])
X    }).
X    {
X    /*notice: now we use the that comes with the node */
X    "id":id,
X    "kind":"node",
X    "label":label,
X    "desc":" ",
X    /* notice: we use the metadata as tags */
X    "tags":$each(metadata, function($v, $k) {$k & ":" & $v}),
X    "parent":"id of thee graph that represents the root",
X    "backgroundImageURL":null,
X    "has_dynamic_notes":false,
X    "is_collapsed":false
X    }
```
X
### Stedi a new playground for jsonata queries:
+ It saves the contents of the frames as part of the URL, so we don't loose it
+ it is easy to share a link to the query
- The debugger gives a wrong position for the error messages.
X
X
X
X
### Next version of the whole jsonata query
In stedy https://stedi.link/kdqY6J0
X
But since I don't want to loose my query here is the backup
X
``` javascript
(
$node_template:=function($id,$label,$metadata,$parentId){{
X    "id":$id,
X    "kind":"node",
X    "label":$label,
X    "desc":" ",
X    "tags":[$each($metadata, function($v, $k) {$k & ":" & $v})],
X    "parent":$parentId,
X    "backgroundImageURL":null,
X    "has_dynamic_notes":false,
X    "is_collapsed":false
X  }
};
X
$rootNode := graph.($node_template(id,label,metadata,null));
X
X
X $n:=graph.nodes.
X    $each(function($n, $id) {
X    /* notice: we are injecting the id into the node */
X    $merge([$n,{"id":$id}])
X    }).(
X      $node_template(id,label,metadata,$rootNode.id)
X    )
X    ;
X
$e:=graph.edges.{
X    "id":source&"-"&target,
X    "kind":"edge",
X    "label":relation,
X    "desc":"desc",
X    "tags":[],
X    "directed":relation?true:false,
X    "weight":metadata.value,
X    "fromId":source,
X    "toId":target
};
X
$const_theme := {
X    "name": "minimal",
X    "bgfill": "#e5e7eb",
X    "grid": false,
X    "snapdist": {
X      "x": 100,
X      "y": 100
X    },
X    "selectionColor": "#1f2937",
X    "highlightColor": "red",
X    "nodefill": "white",
X    "nodelabelstroke": "black",
X    "nodelabelfontsize": 16,
X    "nodenotesfontsize": 16,
X    "nodeborder": "black",
X    "nodeborderradius": 15,
X    "nodeBackgroundImageURL": null,
X    "edgestroke": "#1f2937",
X    "edgeshape": "curved",
X    "edgestroketype": "solid",
X    "font": "PT Mono",
X    "badges": [
X      "",
X      "",
X      "",
X      "",
X      ""
X    ]
X  },
X  "jsondownload": true,
X  "jsonupload": true,
X  "contextmenu": true,
X  "customjson": false,
X  "exportcytoscape": true,
X  "exportsvg": true,
X  "title": "Sample graph",
X  "description": "Compound graphs allow nodes to be nested inside each other.",
X  "contact": "mailto:eshnil22@gmail.com"
};
X
$grapherx_formatted:={
X    "items":$append($rootNode,$n)~>$append($e)},
X    "theme":$const_theme
X    };
)
```

# Wednesday december 20th

I've spen the last two days trying different queries to graph.
But I haven't done any progress :(
X
What I have been wondering is a better way to write this by hand
## Yet another way to write
X
Here is my new query:
https://try.jsonata.org/FFE-gI76l
X
And this is how it looks in yaml:
X
``` sh
X
$ cat ./src/ex4.list_of_objects.yaml | jfq --accept-yaml --query-file ./src/groupSentencesByTypeAndIdTitle.jsonata  | yq --yaml-output
Questions:
X  - root: What should we do about the one ring?
X    answers:
X      - gg: Give it to golumm
X        Questions:
X          - addicted: Isn't he addicted to the ring?
X            answers:
X              - ay: Yes,but so what?
X                Questions:
X                  - yw: So what??!!
X      - gh: Give it to humans
X        pros:
X          - weapon: use the enemys weapon against itself
X          - deserve: we deserve it.
X        cons:
X          - greed: humans greed has failled us once before.
X      - bm: Burn it in mount mordor
X        pros:
X          - ow: its the only way to destroy it
X        cons:
X          - rd: the road is extremely dangerous
X
```
X
This looks very brief to write...
WHich is what I want...
now  I need to learn how move from here
back to a json that can be used for graphs.
X
# Thursday Dec 21st
## I wish I could do pattern matching.
X
I wish I could simply write a query like this:
X
``` javascript
{$id: $label, "pros":$pros, "cons":$cons}
```
X
And apply it to the son document,
and it could give me a result.
X
So I have searched several alternatives... but none seem to work.
X
### [ReJSON](https://github.com/squaremo/rejson)
X
```javscript 
> Json = json:decode("[1, 2, \"foo\", 3]"),
> Pattern = rejson:parse("[1, 2, number *] ^ [S = string]"),
> rejson:match(Pattern, Json).
{ok, [{"S", "foo"}]}
```
X
Observe that `S = string` is where it decides to capture the value.
with the "match" instruction.
X
The problem is what it says here:
X
>A capture cannot appear is as a property name, 
>or (currently) as the operand of an interleave,
>though it can appear in an operand.
X
So what this means is that I cannot use it to match $id property,
which is the difficult part :( 
X
### [Jawk](https://github.com/mohd-akram/jawk)
X
Awk but for json.
X
It seems to me like a query like jsonata but mor imperatiav with For loops and ifs
```bash
$ echo '{"age":10}' | jawk '{print _["age"]}'
10
X
$ echo '{"person":{"name":"Jason"}}' | jawk '{print _["person","name"]}'
Jason
X
$ echo '[4,2,0]' | jawk '{while (++i <= _["length"]) print _[i]}'
4
2
0
X
$ echo '[{"x":6},{"x":7}]' | jawk '{while (++i <= _["length"]) print _[i,"x"]}'
6
7
X
$ printf '{"x":6}\n{"x":7}\n' | jawk '{print _["x"]}'
6
7
X
$ echo '{"name":{"first":"Jason"},"age":25}' | jawk '{
X	keys(o); for (k in o) print k, _[o[k],JSON]
}'
name {"first":"Jason"}
age 25
X
$ echo '{"name":"Jason"}' | jawk '{print _["name",JSON]}'
"Jason"
X
# Try it with real data!
curl -Ls https://api.github.com/repos/onetrueawk/awk |
jawk '{print "id:", _["id"], "owner.id:", _["owner","id"]}'
X
curl -Ls https://api.github.com/repos/onetrueawk/awk/commits |
jawk '{
X	while (++i <= _["length"]) {
X		sha = _[i,"sha"]
X		message = _[i,"commit","message"]
X		l = index(message, "\n")
X		print sha, substr(message, 1, l ? l - 1 : 50)
X	}
}'
X
curl -Ls https://api.github.com/repos/onetrueawk/awk/commits |
jawk '{while (++i <= _["length"]) printf("{\"sha\":%s}\n",_[i,"sha",JSON])}'
```
X
X
# Friday Dec 22
X
## Stumbled to a solution
X
I stumbled on a jsonata query that gives me the desired results:
X
https://try.jsonata.org/lbQzpr17x
X
Emphasis on *stumbled*.
X
So that I asked a query in stackoverflow to find a better way to do it.
X
https://stackoverflow.com/questions/77706465/flatten-nested-structure-by-two-keys
X
Plus I'm also worried that it only works for trees, not graphs.
but It's good enough to help me continue moving:
X
```bash
$ cat ./lord_of_the_rings.yaml | jfq --accept-yaml --query-file ./ibis_to_array_of_objects.jsonata 
[
X  {
X    "kind": "Question",
X    "parent": "null",
X    "id": "root",
X    "label": "What should we do about the one ring?"
X  },
X  {
X    "kind": "Idea",
X    "parent": "root",
X    "id": "gg",
X    "label": "Give it to golumm"
X  },
X  {
X    "kind": "Idea",

X  },

X    "kind": "Idea",

X  },

X    "parent": "bm",

X  },
X  {
X    "kind": "pro",

X    "label": "once and for all"
X  },
X  {
X    "kind": "pro",

```
X
Now I can transform it in to the json for visjs
X
This query was easy
https://try.jsonata.org/9m8IlB-Ge
X
now lets look at it from the command line:
X
```bash
$ cat ./lord_of_the_rings.yaml | jfq --accept-yaml --query-file ./ibis_to_array_of_objects.jsonata  | jfq --query-file ./array_of_objecs_to_visjs.jsonata 
{
X  "data": {
X    "nodes": [
X      {
X        "group": "Question",
X        "id": "root",
X        "label": "What should we do about the one ring?"
X      },
X      {

X      },

X        "id": "root2",
X        "label": "Why do we need to destroy it?"
X      }
X    ],
X    "edges": [
X      {
X        "from": "null",
X        "to": "root"
X      },
X      {
X        "from": "root",
X        "to": "gg"
X      },
X      {

X        "to": "gh"
```

# Saturday Dec 23rd
X
## Why the solution was too easy?
X
The final query that translates from: a doubled nested yaml to flat list of objects was extremely easy to write.
X
Then why did it take me so long to build it?
And more importantly... How can I shorten that time the next time that I have a similar problem?
X
### Wha was the key for the solution?
X  When I had given up, on trying to find the solution for myself I started to write the question in stack overflow.
X
X  And in the process of writing the rigth question I came up with the solution by myself.
X
#### How did you approach asking the question:
X
1. I wrote the well formated input.
2. Then I typed by hand the output that I wanted.
X
!!! Note: But here I actually wrote the *Output that I wanted. NOT the intermediate process that I tought I needed to follow.
X
3. Then I tried to describe the propertie of the output.
X - that the type was the Parent
X - the "parent" was the oldest sibling
X
4. And that the answer was deeply nested. Because I didn't want the solution to be limetd to only two levels deep. So it needed some kind of recursive function. 
X
And with those elemenst was enough to write the solution for myself.
I think this worked well, because jsonata is a declarative language... so
thiking of what I really wanted, as opposed of what I thought where the prosses required to achive it was a good fit.
X
##### How could jsonata work in order to do this?
X
Well maybe the interface of jsonata should be such that:
X
it asks the input, then the desired output.
Then you write your jsonata query,
and it shows you the calculated output.
and then also another window that shows the difference between the expected output,
and the calculated output.
so that you know what is going on.
X
Even better with that interface there could be a genetic algorithm that is testing the json window and calculatingthe output and then given the diffs trying to come up with the algorithm.
X
#### How does this relate to PyRet
In pyret you name the method.
Then write the docs
then the examples (which are the expected outpus given known inputs)
then could be the prec-conditions and post-conditions
and finally the code.
X
which could be seen as:
X
|pyret | jsonata |
|name  with the  goal | comment with the goal|
|exmplaes | testcase|
|example input| input window|
|example output| output window|
| input types| input json-schema|
|pre-conditions| other predicates in the data that are not part of the schema|
| output types | output json-schema |
|post-conditions| other predicates that cannot be part of the schema|
|actual code | actual jsonata query|
| results of the tests | diff between expected output and calculated output|
X
And this relates to programming of functions in general.
X
## I finally understood how to write a paper
This stackoverfow answer about "argument diagramming"
X https://ux.stackexchange.com/a/91762/169709
X
Put me in the pat to discover Toulmind Diagrams for argument diagramming.
X
This lead me to read about Macro-toulmin to write papers.
X
And I thikn I have finally understood how papers should be written!
X
# Sunday Dec 24th 12:19
X
I feel that it's already too late to start working on anything... but common lets do  alittle bit.
X
## How to update my diagram on every file change?
X
### How to generate the correct json for visjs from command line:
X
```bash 
cat ./lord_of_the_rings.yaml | \
jfq --accept-yaml --query-file ./ibis_to_array_of_objects.jsonata  |\
jfq --query-file ./array_of_objecs_to_visjs.jsonata | \
cat <(echo -n "var data=") - <(echo ";") > ibis_for_visjs.js
```
X
### watchexec
is a rust cli command
X
### entr
is a common linux command.
X
``` bash 
$ cat ./lord_of_the_rings.yaml | jfq --accept-yaml --query-file ./ibis_to_array_of_objects.jsonata  | jfq --query-file ./array_of_objecs_to_visjs.jsonata  > 
```
X
X
Now in order to generate the json everytime we change the yaml files.
X
# Tue Dec 26th 2023
X
## Refocus
X
### What do I really want? (for this tool)
X
I want to write any ibis map in vs code and then having a preview window side by side that keeps updating the diagram as I type.
X
Also that I can open that preview windon in its own window so that I can share the map on google meet while typing.
X
Also that I can create a map and from the command line generate an image.
X
### After that?
X
I want to use the VSCode code sharing platform so that I can colaboratelly developed a map.
X
Then maybe use rethink db to develop a collaborative platform that allows a lot of people to work on their own maps. Because with rethink we can save to a central server and the database can push the updates to all the connected clients.
X
Then have each map stored as a json document, so that we can have all the maps linked as json-ld documents that AI can learn from to anwser questions.
X

X        * Complexity: no two parts alike; many states; nonlinear interactions between modules.

# Emitter
X
X  Event emitter component.
X
## Installation
X
```
$ component install component/emitter
```
X
## API
X
### Emitter(obj)
X
X  The `Emitter` may also be used as a mixin. For example
X  a "plain" object may become an emitter, or you may
X  extend an existing prototype.
X
X  As an `Emitter` instance:
X
```js
var Emitter = require('emitter');
var emitter = new Emitter;
emitter.emit('something');
```
X
X  As a mixin:
X
```js
var Emitter = require('emitter');
var user = { name: 'tobi' };
Emitter(user);
X
user.emit('im a user');
```
X
X  As a prototype mixin:
X
```js
var Emitter = require('emitter');
Emitter(User.prototype);
```
X  
### Emitter#on(event, fn)
X
X  Register an `event` handler `fn`.
X
### Emitter#once(event, fn)
X
X  Register a single-shot `event` handler `fn`,
X  removed immediately after it is invoked the
X  first time.
X
### Emitter#off(event, fn)
X
X  * Pass `event` and `fn` to remove a listener.
X  * Pass `event` to remove all listeners on that event.
X  * Pass nothing to remove all listeners on all events.
X
### Emitter#emit(event, ...)
X
X  Emit an `event` with variable option args.
X
### Emitter#listeners(event)
X
X  Return an array of callbacks, or an empty array.
X
### Emitter#hasListeners(event)
X
X  Check if this emitter has `event` handlers.
