# Changelog
X
### 2.0.6, 2015-12-23
- Add Assign method and deprecate merge and extend ([#895](https://github.com/hammerjs/hammer.js/pull/895)[fc01eae](https://github.com/hammerjs/hammer.js/commit/fc01eaea678acc430c664eb374555fbe3d403bdd))
- Expose Hammer on window or self if either is defined to avoid issues when AMD is present but not used. ( [356f795](https://github.com/hammerjs/hammer.js/commit/356f7955b01f3679c29d6c45931679256b45036e))
- Add support for PointerEvent instead of MSPointerEvent if supported. ([#754](https://github.com/hammerjs/hammer.js/issues/754), [439c7a6](https://github.com/hammerjs/hammer.js/commit/439c7a6c46978ab387b4b8289399e904d1c49535))
- Fixed moz-prefix, prefix should be Moz not moz. ([3ea47f3](https://github.com/hammerjs/hammer.js/commit/3ea47f3aebadc9d3bb6bf52bc8402cad135ef8a9))
- Removed non-existant recognizer ([f1c2d3b](https://github.com/hammerjs/hammer.js/commit/f1c2d3bf05f530ae092ecfc2335fceeff0e9eec9))
- Fixed config leaking between instances([189098f](https://github.com/hammerjs/hammer.js/commit/189098ff7736f6ed2fce9a3d3e1f5a3afee085ba))
- Fixed gaps in gesture configs and update tests to match ([70c2902](https://github.com/hammerjs/hammer.js/commit/70c2902d773a750e92ce8c423f8a4165c07eab97))
- Fixed Manager off method ([#768](https://github.com/hammerjs/hammer.js/issues/768), [da49a27](https://github.com/hammerjs/hammer.js/commit/da49a2730779ecc3b4dd147cc418a0df7c70fad9))
- Added compatibility with requirejs optimizer namespaces ( [70075f2](https://github.com/hammerjs/hammer.js/commit/70075f2df1b855f7c6d8d3caac49b9276b88c8d6))
- Made touchaction test zoomable ( [50264a7](https://github.com/hammerjs/hammer.js/commit/50264a70251ca88bbaf7b666401e527eee616de5))
- Fixed preventing default when for `pan-x pan-y` case ( [95eaafa](https://github.com/hammerjs/hammer.js/commit/95eaafadad27bd1b25d20cf976811a451922f1c4))
- Fixed incorrect touch action pan direction ( [a81da57](https://github.com/hammerjs/hammer.js/commit/a81da57a82ebf37e695e7c443e4e2715e7f32856))
- Fixed combined pan-x pan-y to resolve to none ( [fdae07b](https://github.com/hammerjs/hammer.js/commit/fdae07bc2ba3c90aad28da6791b3d5df627bc612))
- Fixed inverted touch-action for pan recognizer ([#728](https://github.com/hammerjs/hammer.js/issues/728), [605bd3b](https://github.com/hammerjs/hammer.js/commit/605bd3beca780be91dd43f9da8b809d155a43d1a))
- Fixed dependency on non standard touch list ordering ([#610](https://github.com/hammerjs/hammer.js/issues/610), [#791](https://github.com/hammerjs/hammer.js/issues/791), [287720a](https://github.com/hammerjs/hammer.js/commit/287720a6e5067e7f28be8b8b3b266d22905361c4))
- Fixed swipe to not trigger after multitouch gesture ([#640](https://github.com/hammerjs/hammer.js/issues/640), [711d8a1](https://github.com/hammerjs/hammer.js/commit/711d8a1df1aa5057ecb536454a36257e3c0d6d91))
- Fixed swipe recognizer to use overall gesture direction and velocity ( [963fe69](https://github.com/hammerjs/hammer.js/commit/963fe697515273fee508414bc29e2656465cea55))
- Fixed getDirection returning reversed direction ( [e40dcde](https://github.com/hammerjs/hammer.js/commit/e40dcde43bdac7a74c8ce5c05a4f62121089cd91))
- Fixed detection of tap when multi touch gestures are present ( [c46cbba](https://github.com/hammerjs/hammer.js/commit/c46cbba1c2cbbf874b59913416858d9dae297e64))
- Fixed incorrect event order ([#824](https://github.com/hammerjs/hammer.js/issues/824), [92f2d76](https://github.com/hammerjs/hammer.js/commit/92f2d76188480d967e738a19cd508d0b94a31329))
- Fixed leaking options between recognizer instances ([#813](https://github.com/hammerjs/hammer.js/issues/813), [af32c9b](https://github.com/hammerjs/hammer.js/commit/af32c9bace3f04bb34bee852ff56a33cc8fc27cd))
- Fixed detection when element has no style attribute ( [5ca6d8c](https://github.com/hammerjs/hammer.js/commit/5ca6d8cbead02c71929a8073e95ddf98e11c0e06))
X
### 2.0.4, 2014-09-28
- Fix IE pointer issue. [#665](https://github.com/hammerjs/hammer.js/pull/665)
- Fix multi-touch at different elements. [#668](https://github.com/hammerjs/hammer.js/pull/668)
- Added experimental [single-user Touch input handler](src/input/singletouch.js). This to improve performance/ux when only a single user has to be supported. Plans are to release 2.1 with this as default, and a settings to enable the multi-user handler.
X
### 2.0.3, 2014-09-10
- Manager.set improvements. 
- Fix requireFailure() call in Manager.options.recognizers. 
- Make DIRECTION_ALL for pan and swipe gestures less blocking.
- Fix Swipe recognizer threshold option.
- Expose the Input classes.
- Added the option `inputClass` to set the used input handler.
X
### 2.0.2, 2014-07-26
- Improved mouse and pointer-events input, now able to move outside the window.
- Added the export name (`Hammer`) as an argument to the wrapper.
- Add the option *experimental* `inputTarget` to change the element that receives the events.
- Improved performance when only one touch being active.
- Fixed the jumping deltaXY bug when going from single to multi-touch.
- Improved velocity calculations.
X
### 2.0.1, 2014-07-15
- Fix issue when no document.body is available
- Added pressup event for the press recognizer
- Removed alternative for Object.create
X
### 2.0.0, 2014-07-11
- Full rewrite of the library.

# Contributing to Hammer.js
X
Looking to contribute something to Hammer.js? **Here's how you can help.**
X
X
## Reporting issues
X
We only accept issues that are bug reports or feature requests. Bugs must be
isolated and reproducible problems that can be fixed within the Hammer.js.
Please read the following guidelines before opening any issue.
X
1. [**Read the documentation**](https://hammerjs.github.io)
X
2. **Search for existing issues.** We get a lot of duplicate issues, and you'd
help us out a lot by first checking if someone else has reported the same issue.
Moreover, the issue may have already been resolved with a fix available. Also
take a look if your problem is explained at the Wiki.
X
3. **Create an isolated and reproducible test case.** Be sure the problem exists
in Hammer's code with a reduced test case that should be included in each bug
report.
X
4. **Include a live example.** Make use of jsFiddle or jsBin to share your
isolated test cases. Also, a screen capture would work, with tools like LICEcap.
X
5. **Share as much information as possible.** Include operating system and
version, browser and version, version of Hammer.js, customized or vanilla build,
etc. where appropriate. Also include steps to reproduce the bug.
X
## Pull requests
X
1. Changes must be done in `/src` files, never just the compiled files. Also, don't 
commit the compiled files.
X
2. Try not to pollute your pull request with unintended changes. Keep them simple
and small
X
3. Try to share which browsers your code has been tested in before submitting a
pull request
X
4. Write tests for your code, these can be found in `/tests`.

# Hammer.js 2.0.6
X
[![Build Status](https://travis-ci.org/hammerjs/hammer.js.svg)](https://travis-ci.org/hammerjs/hammer.js)
X
## Support, Questions, and Collaboration
X
[![Slack Status](https://hammerjs.herokuapp.com/badge.svg)](https://hammerjs.herokuapp.com/)
X
## Documentation
X
Visit [hammerjs.github.io](http://hammerjs.github.io) for detailed documentation.
X
```js
// get a reference to an element
var stage = document.getElementById('stage');
X
// create a manager for that element
var mc = new Hammer.Manager(stage);
X
// create a recognizer
var Rotate = new Hammer.Rotate();
X
// add the recognizer
mc.add(Rotate);
X
// subscribe to events
mc.on('rotate', function(e) {
X    // do something cool
X    var rotation = Math.round(e.rotation);    
X    stage.style.transform = 'rotate('+rotation+'deg)';
});
```
X
An advanced demo is available here: [http://codepen.io/runspired/full/ZQBGWd/](http://codepen.io/runspired/full/ZQBGWd/)
X
X
## Contributing
X
Read the [contributing guidelines](./CONTRIBUTING.md).
X
For PRs.
X
- Use [Angular Style commit messages](https://github.com/angular/angular.js/blob/v1.4.8/CONTRIBUTING.md#commit)
- Rebase your PR branch when necessary
- If you add a feature or fix a bug, please add or fix any necessary tests.
- If a new feature, open a docs PR to go with.
X
## Building
X
You can get the pre-build versions from the Hammer.js website, or do this by yourself running 
`npm install -g grunt-cli && npm install && grunt build`

keycharm
========
X
Easy and free library for binding keys.
X
Keycharm is on npm so you can install it with:
```
npm install keycharm
```
X
X
Example:
X
```
var keys = keycharm(options);
X
keys.bind("a", function () {}, 'keydown'); // key, callback function, 'keydown' or 'keyup'
```
X
Available options (all are optional):
```
{
X    container: document.getElementById("element"), // optional div to bind keycharm to. It will NEED a tabindex. When not supplied, this defaults to window.
X    preventDefault: true/false // default value: false;
}
```
X
Supported keys:
X
```
'a'-'z', 'A'-'Z', '0'-'9', 'F1'-'F12', 'space', 'enter', 'ctrl', 'alt', 'tab', 'shift', 
'delete', 'esc', 'backspace', '-','=', '[', ']', 'left', 'up', 'right', 'down', 'pageup', 'pagedown'
X
numpad: 'num0'-'num9', 'num/', 'num*', 'num-', 'num+', 'num.'
```
X
Each initiation of keycharm has its own bindings to the key events.
X
Available methods:
X
```
X.bind(key, callback, [type]);               // bind key, type = 'keydown' or 'keyup', default type = keydown.
X.unbind(key, [callback], [type]);           // unbind key,  type = 'keydown' or 'keyup', default type = keydown. No callback deletes all bound callbacks from key
X.reset();                                   // remove all bound keys
X.destroy();                                 // remove all bound keys and the event listeners of keycharm
X.getKey(event);                             // get the key label of the event
X.bindAll(function, 'keydown' or 'keyup');   // bind all keys to this function, could be used for testing or demos.
```
X
Keycharm is Dual-licensed with both the Apache 2.0 license as well as the MIT license. I'll leave it up to the user to pick which one they prefer.

under dist/ folder. This might alleviate issues with finding the `./locale
subfolder for loading locales. This might also mean now webpack will bundle all
locales automatically, unless told otherwise.

### 2.10.5 [See full changelog](https://gist.github.com/ichernev/6ec13ac7efc396da44b2)
X
- Release July 26, 2015
X
Important changes:
* [#2357](https://github.com/moment/moment/pull/2357) Improve unit bubbling for ISO dates
X  this fixes day to year conversions to work around end-of-year (~365 days). As
X  a side effect 365 days is 11 months and 30 days, and 366 days is one year.
* [#2438](https://github.com/moment/moment/pull/2438) Fix inconsistent moment.min and moment.max results
X  Return invalid result if any of the inputs is invalid
* [#2494](https://github.com/moment/moment/pull/2494) Fix two digit year parsing with YYYY format
X  This brings the benefits of YY to YYYY
* [#2368](https://github.com/moment/moment/pull/2368) perf: use faster form of copying dates, across the board improvement
X
X

### 2.8.0 [See changelog](https://gist.github.com/ichernev/ac3899324a5fa6c8c9b4)
X
- Release July 31, 2014
X
* incompatible changes
X    * [#1761](https://github.com/moment/moment/issues/1761): moments created without a language are no longer following the global language, in case it changes. Only newly created moments take the global language by default. In case you're affected by this, wait, comment on [#1797](https://github.com/moment/moment/issues/1797) and wait for a proper reimplementation
X    * [#1642](https://github.com/moment/moment/issues/1642): 45 days is no longer "a month" according to humanize, cutoffs for month, and year have changed. Hopefully your code does not depend on a particular answer from humanize (which it shouldn't anyway)
X    * [#1784](https://github.com/moment/moment/issues/1784): if you use the human readable English datetime format in a weird way (like storing them in a database) that would break when the format changes you're at risk.
X
* deprecations (old behavior will be dropped in 3.0)
X    * [#1761](https://github.com/moment/moment/issues/1761) `lang` is renamed to `locale`, `langData` -> `localeData`. Also there is now `defineLocale` that should be used when creating new locales
X    * [#1763](https://github.com/moment/moment/issues/1763) `add(unit, value)` and `subtract(unit, value)` are now deprecated. Use `add(value, unit)` and `subtract(value, unit)` instead.
X    * [#1759](https://github.com/moment/moment/issues/1759) rename `duration.toIsoString` to `duration.toISOString`. The js standard library and moment's `toISOString` follow that convention.
X
* new locales
X    * [#1789](https://github.com/moment/moment/issues/1789) Tibetan (bo)
X    * [#1786](https://github.com/moment/moment/issues/1786) Africaans (af)
X    * [#1778](https://github.com/moment/moment/issues/1778) Burmese (my)
X    * [#1727](https://github.com/moment/moment/issues/1727) Belarusian (be)
X
* bugfixes, locale bugfixes, performance improvements, features
X

### 2.0.0 [See changelog](https://gist.github.com/timrwood/e72f2eef320ed9e37c51)
X
- Release Feb 9, 2013
X
Added short form localized tokens.
X
Added ability to define language a string should be parsed in.
X
Added support for reversed add/subtract arguments.
X
Added support for `endOf('week')` and `startOf('week')`.
X
Fixed the logic for `moment#diff(Moment, 'months')` and `moment#diff(Moment, 'years')`
X
`moment#diff` now floors instead of rounds.
X
Normalized `moment#toString`.
X
Added `isSame`, `isAfter`, and `isBefore` methods.
X
Added better week support.
X
Added `moment#toJSON`
X
Bugfix: Fixed parsing of first century dates
X
Bugfix: Parsing 10Sep2001 should work as expected
X
Bugfix: Fixed weirdness with `moment.utc()` parsing.
X
Changed language ordinal method to return the number + ordinal instead of just the ordinal.
X
Changed two digit year parsing cutoff to match strptime.
X
Removed `moment#sod` and `moment#eod` in favor of `moment#startOf` and `moment#endOf`.
X
Removed `moment.humanizeDuration()` in favor of `moment.duration().humanize()`.
X
Removed the lang data objects from the top level namespace.
X
Duplicate `Date` passed to `moment()` instead of referencing it.
X

### 1.7.0 [See discussion](https://github.com/timrwood/moment/issues/288)
X
- Release Jul 26, 2012
X
Added `moment.fn.endOf()` and `moment.fn.startOf()`.
X
Added validation via `moment.fn.isValid()`.
X
Made formatting method 3x faster. http://jsperf.com/momentjs-cached-format-functions
X
Add support for month/weekday callbacks in `moment.fn.format()`
X
Added instance specific languages.
X
Added two letter weekday abbreviations with the formatting token `dd`.
X
Various language updates.
X
Various bugfixes.
X
### 1.6.0 [See discussion](https://github.com/timrwood/moment/pull/268)
X
- Release Apr 26, 2012
X
Added Durations.
X
Revamped parser to support parsing non-separated strings (YYYYMMDD vs YYYY-MM-DD).
X
Added support for millisecond parsing and formatting tokens (S SS SSS)
X
Added a getter for `moment.lang()`
X
Various bugfixes.
X
There are a few things deprecated in the 1.6.0 release.
X
1. The format tokens `z` and `zz` (timezone abbreviations like EST CST MST etc) will no longer be supported. Due to inconsistent browser support, we are unable to consistently produce this value. See [this issue](https://github.com/timrwood/moment/issues/162) for more background.
X
2. The method `moment.fn.native` is deprecated in favor of `moment.fn.toDate`. There continue to be issues with Google Closure Compiler throwing errors when using `native`, even in valid instances.
X
3. The way to customize am/pm strings is being changed. This would only affect you if you created a custom language file. For more information, see [this issue](https://github.com/timrwood/moment/pull/222).
X

### 0.6.0

X

Made parse from string and single format 25% faster.

- Release Jun 17, 2011
X
Bugfix for [issue 5](https://github.com/timrwood/underscore.date/pull/5).
X
### 0.5.0
X
- Release Jun 13, 2011
X
Dropped the redundant `_date.date()` in favor of `_date()`.
Removed `_date.now()`, as it is a duplicate of `_date()` with no parameters.
Removed `_date.isLeapYear(yearNumber)`. Use `_date([yearNumber]).isLeapYear()` instead.
Exposed customization options through the `_date.relativeTime`, `_date.weekdays`, `_date.weekdaysShort`, `_date.months`, `_date.monthsShort`, and `_date.ordinal` variables instead of the `_date.customize()` function.
X
### 0.4.1
X
- Release May 9, 2011
X
Added date input formats for input strings.
X
### 0.4.0
X
- Release May 9, 2011
X
Added underscore.date to npm. Removed dependencies on underscore.
X
### 0.3.2
X
- Release Apr 9, 2011
X
Added `'z'` and `'zz'` to `_.date().format()`. Cleaned up some redundant code to trim off some bytes.
X
### 0.3.1
X
- Release Mar 25, 2011
X
Cleaned up the namespace. Moved all date manipulation and display functions to the _.date() object.
X
### 0.3.0
X
- Release Mar 25, 2011
X
Switched to the Underscore methodology of not mucking with the native objects' prototypes.
Made chaining possible.
X

# [Moment.js](http://momentjs.com/)
X
[![NPM version][npm-version-image]][npm-url]
[![NPM downloads][npm-downloads-image]][npm-downloads-url]
[![MIT License][license-image]][license-url]
[![Build Status][travis-image]][travis-url]
[![Coverage Status][coveralls-image]][coveralls-url]
[![FOSSA Status][fossa-badge-image]][fossa-badge-url]
[![SemVer compatibility][semver-image]][semver-url]
X
A JavaScript date library for parsing, validating, manipulating, and formatting dates.
X
## Project Status
X
Moment.js is a legacy project, now in maintenance mode.  In most cases, you should choose a different library.
X
For more details and recommendations, please see [Project Status](https://momentjs.com/docs/#/-project-status/) in the docs.
X
*Thank you.*
X
## Resources
X
- [Documentation](https://momentjs.com/docs/)
- [Changelog](CHANGELOG.md)
- [Stack Overflow](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/tagged/momentjs)
X
## License
X
Moment.js is freely distributable under the terms of the [MIT license][license-url].
X

# History
X
## 2020-10-14, version 1.5.0
X
- Add ESM support. Thanks @mojoaxel.
X
X
## 2019-07-27, version 1.4.7
X
- Upgraded to `hammerjs@2.0.8`. Thanks @mojoaxel.
X
X
## 2016-03-05, version 1.4.6
X
- Fixed #6: stopPropagation not binding to the original event.
X
X
## 2016-01-13, version 1.4.5
X
- Made `propagating-hammerjs` more robust against removing/attaching a DOM
X  element in the DOM whilst executing a touch event of the DOM element itself.
X
X
## 2016-01-04, version 1.4.4
X
- Upgraded to Hammer.js v2.0.6.
X  - Replaced usage of `Hammer.extend` with `Hammer.assign`.
- Fixed not working in case of multiple instances of propagating-hammerjs on
X  the same DOM element. Thanks @jsdw.
X
X
## 2015-06-04, version 1.4.3
X
- Fixed `dragend` events not being emitted correctly in case of multiple
X  nested handlers.
X
X
## 2015-06-02, version 1.4.2
X
- Fixed not being able to overload options when having overridden the global
X  Hammer instance.
X
X
## 2015-04-20, version 1.4.1
X
- Fixed not being able to handle both a tap and double tap.
X
X
## 2015-04-17, version 1.4.0
X
- Extended the option `preventDefault` with values `'mouse'`, `'touch'`,
X  and `'pen'` to prevent default behavior for a specific type of device.
X
X
## 2015-04-14, version 1.3.0
X
- Created an option `preventDefault` to enforce preventing the default browser
X  behavior.
- Fixed propagation not being handled correctly when the mouse pointer is
X  being dragged outside the parent div.
X
X
## 2015-02-09, version 1.2.2
X
- Fixed #2, the `emit` method not working.
X
X
## 2015-01-29, version 1.2.1
X
- Removed using top level `this`, attaching `propagating` immediately to
X  `window instead`.
X
X
## 2015-01-05, version 1.2.0
X
- Added an event property `event.firstTarget`, always containing the element
X  where a gesture started.
- Fixed the `hammer.input` event blocking the emit of real events.
- Fixed `panend` not being emitted when `pan` was used too.
X
X
## 2015-01-02, version 1.1.1
X
- Fixed the module not working via commonjs.
X
X
## 2014-12-30, version 1.1.0
X
- Added support for applying `propagating` to the Hammer constructor.
X
X
## 2014-12-30, version 1.0.0
X
- Initial, fully functional release.

# propagating-hammerjs
X
Extend [hammer.js](https://github.com/hammerjs/hammer.js) v2 with event propagation.
X
## Features
X
- Events emitted by hammer will propagate in order from child to parent
X  elements.
- Events are extended with a function `event.stopPropagation()` to stop
X  propagation to parent elements.
- Events are extended with a property `event.firstTarget` containing the
X  element where a gesture started.
- Supports changing and rearranging the HTML DOM on the fly.
- Load via commonjs, AMD, or as a plain old JavaScript file.
X
## Install
X
```sh
npm install propagating-hammerjs
```
X
## Load
X
### Browser
X
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
X  <script src="https://unpkg.com/hammerjs@latest/hammer.js"></script>
X  <script src="https://unpkg.com/propagating-hammerjs@latest/propagating.js"></script>
X  <script>
X    function init() {
X      var hammer = propagating(new Hammer(element));
X    }
X  </script>
</head>
<body>
</body>
</html>
```
X
### Commonjs (e.g. Node.js, Browserify)
X
```js
var Hammer = require('hammerjs');
var propagating = require('propagating-hammerjs');
X
function init() {
X  var hammer = propagating(new Hammer(element));
}
```
X
### ESM (e.g. ES6, typescript)
X
```typescript
import Hammer from 'hammerjs';
import propagating from 'propagating-hammerjs';
X
function init() {
X  const hammer = propagating(new Hammer(element));
}
```
X
## Use
X
To extend individual hammer.js instances with event propagation:
X
```js
var hammer = propagating(new Hammer(element));
```
X
To extend the global hammer.js constructor
X
```js
Hammer = propagating(Hammer);
```
X
## Examples
X
Here a basic usage example.
More examples are available in the folder [/examples](./examples/).
X
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
X  <script src="node_modules/hammerjs/hammer.js"></script>
X  <script src="propagating.js"></script>
X  <style>
X    div     {border: 1px solid black;}
X    #parent {width: 400px; height: 400px; background: lightgreen;}
X    #child  {width: 200px; height: 200px; background: yellow; margin: 10px;}
X  </style>
</head>
<body>
X
<div id="parent">
X  parent
X  <div id="child">
X    child
X  </div>
</div>
X
<script>
X  var parent = document.getElementById('parent');
X  var hammer1 = propagating(new Hammer(parent))
X      .on('tap', function (event) {
X        alert('tap on parent');
X      });
X
X  var child = document.getElementById('child');
X  var hammer2 = propagating(new Hammer(child))
X      .on('tap', function (event) {
X        alert('tap on child');
X
X        // stop propagation from child to parent
X        event.stopPropagation();
X      });
</script>
</body>
</html>
```
X
## API
X
Construction:
X
```typescript
propagating(hammer: Hammer.Manager, options?: {
X  preventDefault?: true | 'mouse' | 'touch' | 'pen'
}): Hammer.Manager
```
X
### parameters
X
- `hammer: Hammer.Manager` An hammer instance or the global hammer constructor.
X
- `options: Object` An optional object with options. Available options:
X
X  - `preventDefault: true | 'mouse' | 'touch' | 'pen'`. Optional.
X    Enforce preventing the default browser behavior. Cannot be set to `false`.
X
### returns
X
Returns the same hammer instance with extended functionality.
X
### events
X
The emitted [hammer.js events](http://hammerjs.github.io/api/#event-object) are
extended with:
X
- `event.stopPropagation()`
X
X  If called, the event will not further propagate the elements parents.
X
- `event.firstTarget`
X
X  Contains the HTML element where a gesture started (where as `event.target`
X  contains the element where the pointer is right now).
X
## Develop
X
To generate the UMD bundle for commonjs and browser, run:
X
```sh
npm run build
```
X
## License
X
MIT

- Fixed #1406, control nodes are now drawn immediately without a second redraw.
- Fixed #1404, made the array returned by findNode match the docs.
- Added #1138, enable the user to define the color of the shadows for nodes and edges.
- Fixed #1528, #1278, avoided ID's being cast to string for methods that return ID's as well as storePositions casting to string.
- Fixed upscaling when the window size increases.
- Accepted pull request #1544, thanks @felixhayashi!
- Fixed documented bug in #1544.

## 2015-05-22, version 4.0.0
X
### General
X
- Changed the build scripts to include a transpilation of ES6 to ES5
X  (using http://babel.org), so we can use ES6 features in the vis.js code.
X  When creating a custom bundle using browserify, one now needs to add a
X  transform step using `babelify`, this is described in README.md.
X
### Timeline
X
- Integrated an option configurator and validator.
- Implemented option `multiselect`, which is false by default.
- Added method `setData({groups: groups, items: items})`.
- Fixed range items not being displayed smaller than 10 pixels (twice the
X  padding). In order to have overflowing text, one should now apply css style
X  `.vis.timeline .item.range { overflow: visible; }` instead of
X  `.vis.timeline .item.range .content { overflow: visible; }`.
X  See example 18_range_overflow.html.
- Fixed invalid css names for time axis grid, renamed hours class names from
X  `4-8h` to `h4-h8`.
- Deprecated option `showCustomTime`. Use method `addCustomTime()` instead.
- Deprecated event `finishedRedraw` as it's redundant.
- Renamed option `animate` to `animation`, and changed it to be either a boolean
X  or an object `{duration: number, easingFunction: string}`.
- Fixed #831: items losing selection when their type changed.
X
### Graph2d
X
- New option structure.
- Cleaned up docs.
- Fixed #628: stacking order.
- Fixed #624: sorting order.
- Fixed #616: stacking with negative bars.
- Fixed #728: alignment issues.
- Fixed #716: Height of graph `2px` too large when configuring a fixed height.
X
### Network
X
The network has been completely rewritten. The new modular setup using ES6 classes makes
it future proof for maintainability, extendability and clarity. A summary of new features:
- New examples, categorized by topic.
- New docs.
- New option structure, adhering to the modular setup on the backend.
- New events for user interaction.
- New render events for drawing custom elements on the canvas.
- New physics events for making a loading bar during stabilization.
- A lot of new methods that make extending easier.
- Manipulation system now works without the UI neccesarily.
- Nodes and edges can cast shadows.
- Configurator system to dynamically change almost all options.
- Validator has been created for the network's options, warning you about typo's and suggesting alternatives.
- Diamond shape for nodes.
- Unified the label code so edges and nodes have the same label settings.
- InheritColors for edges can be set to both, making a gradient fade between two node colors.
- Redesigned the clustering system giving full control over it.
- Random seed can be saved so the network will be the same every time you start it.
- New physics solver based on ForceAtlas2 as implemented in gephi.]
- New avoidOverlap option for physics.
- Many, many bugfixes.
X
X
### DataSet
X
- Dropped support for Google visualization DataTable.
- Dropped support for appending data returned by `DataSet.get()` to an existing
X  Array or DataTable.
X
X

- Added opacity option to edges. Opacity is only used for the unselected state.

X
- Fixed mass = 0 for nodes.
- Revamped the options system. You can globally set options (network.setOptions) to update settings of nodes and edges that have not been specifically defined by the individual nodes and edges.
- Disabled inheritColor when color information is set on an edge.
- Tweaked examples.
- Removed the global length property for edges. The edgelength is part of the physics system. Therefore, you have to change the springLength of the physics system to change the edge length. Individual edge lengths can still be defined.
- Removed global edge length definition form examples.
- Removed onclick and onrelease for navigation and switched to Hammer.js (fixing touchscreen interaction with navigation).
- Fixed error on adding an edge without having created the nodes it should be connected to (in the case of dynamic smooth curves).

# vis.js (deprecated!)
X
:exclamation: **This project is not maintained anymore! (See [Issue #4259](http://github.com/almende/vis/issues/4259#issue-412107497) for details)**<br/>**We welcome you to use the libraries from the [visjs community](https://www.github.com/visjs) from now on.**
X
---
X
Vis.js is a dynamic, browser based visualization library.
The library is designed to be easy to use, handle large amounts
of dynamic data, and enable manipulation of the data.
The library consists of the following components:
X
- DataSet and DataView. A flexible key/value based data set. Add, update, and
X  remove items. Subscribe on changes in the data set. A DataSet can filter and
X  order items, and convert fields of items.
- DataView. A filtered and/or formatted view on a DataSet.
- Graph2d. Plot data on a timeline with lines or barcharts.
- Graph3d. Display data in a three dimensional graph.
- Network. Display a network (force directed graph) with nodes and edges.
- Timeline. Display different types of data on a timeline.
X
The vis.js library was initially developed by [Almende B.V](http://almende.com).
X
## Install
X
Install via npm:
X
```sh
npm install vis
```
X
Install via bower:
X
```sh
bower install vis
```
X
Link via cdnjs: https://cdnjs.com/libraries/vis
X
Or download the library from the github project:
[https://github.com/almende/vis.git](https://github.com/almende/vis.git).
X
## Load
X
To use a component, include the javascript and css files of vis in your web page:
X
```html
<!DOCTYPE HTML>
<html>
<head>
X  <script src="vis/dist/vis.min.js"></script>
X  <link href="vis/dist/vis.min.css" rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" />
</head>
<body>
X  <script type="text/javascript">
X    // ... load a visualization
X  </script>
</body>
</html>
```
X
or load vis.js using require.js. Note that vis.css must be loaded too.
X
```js
require.config({
X  paths: {
X    vis: 'path/to/vis/dist',
X  }
});
require(['vis'], function (math) {
X  // ... load a visualization
});
```
X
A timeline can be instantiated as:
X
```js
var timeline = new vis.Timeline(container, data, options);
```
X
Where `container` is an HTML element, `data` is an Array with data or a DataSet,
and `options` is an optional object with configuration options for the
component.
X
## Example
X
A basic example on loading a Timeline is shown below. More examples can be
found in the [examples directory](https://github.com/almende/vis/tree/master/examples)
of the project.
X
```html
<!DOCTYPE HTML>
<html>
<head>
X  <title>Timeline basic demo</title>
X  <script src="vis/dist/vis.min.js"></script>
X  <link href="vis/dist/vis.min.css" rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" />
X
X  <style type="text/css">
X    body, html {
X      font-family: sans-serif;
X    }
X  </style>
</head>
<body>
<div id="visualization"></div>
X
<script type="text/javascript">
X  var container = document.getElementById('visualization');
X  var data = [
X    {id: 1, content: 'item 1', start: '2013-04-20'},
X    {id: 2, content: 'item 2', start: '2013-04-14'},
X    {id: 3, content: 'item 3', start: '2013-04-18'},
X    {id: 4, content: 'item 4', start: '2013-04-16', end: '2013-04-19'},
X    {id: 5, content: 'item 5', start: '2013-04-25'},
X    {id: 6, content: 'item 6', start: '2013-04-27'}
X  ];
X  var options = {};
X  var timeline = new vis.Timeline(container, data, options);
</script>
</body>
</html>
```
X
## Build
X
To build the library from source, clone the project from github
X
```sh
git clone git://github.com/almende/vis.git
```
X
The source code uses the module style of node (require and module.exports) to
organize dependencies. To install all dependencies and build the library,
run `npm install` in the root of the project.
X
```sh
cd vis
npm install
```
X
Then, the project can be build running:
X
```sh
npm run build
```
X
To automatically rebuild on changes in the source files, once can use
X
```sh
npm run watch
```
X
This will both build and minify the library on changes. Minifying is relatively
slow, so when only the non-minified library is needed, one can use the
`watch-dev` script instead:
X
```sh
npm run watch-dev
```
X
## Custom builds
X
The folder `dist` contains bundled versions of vis.js for direct use in the browser. These bundles contain all the visualizations and include external dependencies such as *hammer.js* and *moment.js*.
X
The source code of vis.js consists of commonjs modules, which makes it possible to create custom bundles using tools like [Browserify](http://browserify.org/) or [Webpack](http://webpack.github.io/). This can be bundling just one visualization like the Timeline, or bundling vis.js as part of your own browserified web application.
X
*Note that hammer.js version 2 is required as of v4.*
X
### Prerequisites
X
Before you can do a build:
X
- Install *node.js* and *npm* on your system: https://nodejs.org/
- Install the following modules using npm: `browserify`, `babelify`, and `uglify-js`:
X
```sh
[sudo] npm install -g browserify babelify uglify-js
```
X
- Download or clone the vis.js project:
X
```sh
git clone https://github.com/almende/vis.git
```
X
- Install the dependencies of vis.js by running `npm install` in the root of the project:
X
```sh
cd vis
npm install
```
X
### Examples of custom builds
X
#### Example 1: Bundle only a single visualization type
X
For example, to create a bundle with just the Timeline and DataSet, create an index file named **custom.js** in the root of the project, containing:
X
```js
exports.DataSet = require('./lib/DataSet');
exports.Timeline = require('./lib/timeline/Timeline');
```
X
Then create a custom bundle using browserify, like:
X
```sh
browserify custom.js -t [ babelify --presets [es2015] ] -o dist/vis-custom.js -s vis
```
X
This will generate a custom bundle *vis-custom.js*, which exposes the namespace `vis` containing only `DataSet` and `Timeline`. The generated bundle can be minified using uglifyjs:
X
```sh
uglifyjs dist/vis-custom.js -o dist/vis-custom.min.js
```
X
The custom bundle can now be loaded like:
X
```html
<!DOCTYPE HTML>
<html>
<head>
X  <script src="dist/vis-custom.min.js"></script>
X  <link href="dist/vis.min.css" rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" />
</head>
<body>
X  ...
</body>
</html>
```
X
#### Example 2: Exclude external libraries
X
The default bundle `vis.js` is standalone and includes external dependencies such as *hammer.js* and *moment.js*. When these libraries are already loaded by the application, vis.js does not need to include these dependencies itself too. To build a custom bundle of vis.js excluding *moment.js* and *hammer.js*, run browserify in the root of the project:
X
```sh
browserify index.js -t [ babelify --presets [es2015] ] -o dist/vis-custom.js -s vis -x moment -x hammerjs
```
X
This will generate a custom bundle *vis-custom.js*, which exposes the namespace `vis`, and has *moment.js* and *hammer.js* excluded. The generated bundle can be minified with uglifyjs:
X
```sh
uglifyjs dist/vis-custom.js -o dist/vis-custom.min.js
```
X
The custom bundle can now be loaded as:
X
```html
<!DOCTYPE HTML>
<html>
<head>
X  <!-- load external dependencies -->
X  <script src="http://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/moment.js/2.17.1/moment.min.js"></script>
X  <script src="http://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/hammer.js/2.0.8/hammer.min.js"></script>
X
X  <!-- load vis.js -->
X  <script src="dist/vis-custom.min.js"></script>
X  <link href="dist/vis.min.css" rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" />
</head>
<body>
X  ...
</body>
</html>
```
X
#### Example 3: Bundle vis.js as part of your (commonjs) application
X
When writing a web application with commonjs modules, vis.js can be packaged automatically into the application. Create a file **app.js** containing:
X
```js
var moment = require('moment');
var DataSet = require('vis/lib/DataSet');
var Timeline = require('vis/lib/timeline/Timeline');
X
var container = document.getElementById('visualization');
var data = new DataSet([
X  {id: 1, content: 'item 1', start: moment('2013-04-20')},
X  {id: 2, content: 'item 2', start: moment('2013-04-14')},
X  {id: 3, content: 'item 3', start: moment('2013-04-18')},
X  {id: 4, content: 'item 4', start: moment('2013-04-16'), end: moment('2013-04-19')},
X  {id: 5, content: 'item 5', start: moment('2013-04-25')},
X  {id: 6, content: 'item 6', start: moment('2013-04-27')}
]);
var options = {};
var timeline = new Timeline(container, data, options);
```
X
The application can be bundled and minified:
X
```sh
browserify app.js -o dist/app-bundle.js -t babelify
uglifyjs dist/app-bundle.js -o dist/app-bundle.min.js
```
X
And loaded into a webpage:
X
```html
<!DOCTYPE HTML>
<html>
<head>
X  <link href="node_modules/vis/dist/vis.min.css" rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" />
</head>
<body>
X  <div id="visualization"></div>
X  <script src="dist/app-bundle.min.js"></script>
</body>
</html>
```
X
#### Example 4: Integrate vis.js components directly in your webpack build
X
You can integrate e.g. the timeline component directly in you webpack build.
Therefor you can e.g. import the component-files from root direcory (starting with "index-").
X
```js
import { DataSet, Timeline } from 'vis/index-timeline-graph2d';
X
var container = document.getElementById('visualization');
var data = new DataSet();
var timeline = new Timeline(container, data, {});
```
X
To get this to work you'll need to add some babel-loader-setting to your webpack-config:
X
```js
module: {
X  module: {
X    rules: [{
X      test: /node_modules[\\\/]vis[\\\/].*\.js$/,
X      loader: 'babel-loader',
X      query: {
X        cacheDirectory: true,
X        presets: [ "babel-preset-es2015" ].map(require.resolve),
X        plugins: [
X          "transform-es3-property-literals", // #2452
X          "transform-es3-member-expression-literals", // #2566
X          "transform-runtime" // #2566
X        ]
X      }
X    }]
X  }
}
```
X
There is also an [demo-project](https://github.com/mojoaxel/vis-webpack-demo) showing the integration of vis.js using webpack.
X
## Test
X
To test the library, install the project dependencies once:
X
```sh
npm install
```
X
Then run the tests:
X
```sh
npm run test
```
X
